a professor of neurobiology

00:00:11.910 --> 00:00:15.080
and ophthalmology at
Stanford School of Medicine.

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:18.530
Today, we continue in our
discussion about sensation

00:00:18.530 --> 00:00:20.370
or how we sense things.

00:00:20.370 --> 00:00:22.920
On previous episodes, we
talked about sensing light

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:25.620
and sound waves for things
like vision and hearing.

00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:28.290
Today, we are going to
talk about our sense

00:00:28.290 --> 00:00:30.453
of self or what's called interoception.

00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:33.360
Interoception is our sensing

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:36.870
of our internal landscape,
things like our heartbeat,

00:00:36.870 --> 00:00:41.580
our breathing, and our gut,
how full our gut might happen

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:44.200
to be, or how empty our
gut might happen to be.

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:47.630
But also our inner landscape
with respect to chemistry,

00:00:47.630 --> 00:00:52.630
how acidic, or how good or
bad we feel on the inside.

00:00:53.090 --> 00:00:54.240
This discussion about sense

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:57.010
of self and interoception
has many important,

00:00:57.010 --> 00:00:58.340
actionable items that relate

00:00:58.340 --> 00:01:00.960
to bodily health and brain health,

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:02.253
and believe it or not,

00:01:03.246 --> 00:01:07.530
our ability to perform well
or perform poorly in life.

00:01:07.530 --> 00:01:11.810
Indeed, it has profound influence
on our rates of healing.

00:01:11.810 --> 00:01:14.980
So today we are going to talk
about all the aspects of our

00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:18.030
inner landscape and how our
brain and body communicate.

00:01:18.030 --> 00:01:20.360
And there will be many
actionable protocols

00:01:20.360 --> 00:01:22.240
as we go along that discussion.

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:24.770
Before we begin our discussion
about sense of self,

00:01:24.770 --> 00:01:27.290
I want to highlight some very
recently published research

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:31.800
findings that I believe
are immediately actionable

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:34.000
and that everybody should be aware of.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:35.860
These are data that were
published by my colleague,

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:37.470
Justin Sonnenberg's laboratory

00:01:37.470 --> 00:01:39.490
at Stanford University School of Medicine,

00:01:39.490 --> 00:01:41.920
and the data were published
in the Journal Cell,

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:45.660
which is a very high
stringency cell press journal.

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:47.700
So phenomenal data.

00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:51.360
What this study showed was
that individuals given a high

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:55.550
fiber diet actually
experienced less diversity

00:01:55.550 --> 00:01:57.870
of what's called the gut microbiome.

00:01:57.870 --> 00:02:00.670
The number of positive or
health promoting bacteria

00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:04.090
in the gut was actually
reduced by a high fiber diet,

00:02:04.090 --> 00:02:06.910
whereas individuals that ate just a couple

00:02:06.910 --> 00:02:09.400
of servings of fermented food each day,

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:13.400
experience important
and beneficial increases

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:15.300
in anti-inflammatory markers.

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:17.830
And that could be traced
back to improvements

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:21.470
in the gut microbiome
diversity, the diversity

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:23.550
of bugs, literally little bacteria

00:02:23.550 --> 00:02:26.405
that live in the gut,
which might sound bad,

00:02:26.405 --> 00:02:28.290
but they are actually
very health promoting.

00:02:28.290 --> 00:02:31.210
I'm going to get into all
the details of this study

00:02:31.210 --> 00:02:32.540
later in the episode,

00:02:32.540 --> 00:02:34.690
but I just wanted to
emphasize these findings

00:02:34.690 --> 00:02:36.680
because they are immediately actionable.

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:38.880
I think for most people
ingesting one or two servings

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:43.010
of fermented food each day is
reasonable and does not bring

00:02:43.010 --> 00:02:46.500
with it tremendous costs or
tremendous inconvenience.

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:49.340
And I think many people are
ingesting high fiber diets

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:50.940
thinking that that's the best way

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:53.000
to improve their gut microbiome.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.300
So while these data may prove
to be controversial among the

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:58.680
folks out there in the
nutrition community,

00:02:58.680 --> 00:03:00.790
that really high fiber diet,

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:03.380
I want to just emphasize that
these data were looked at

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:04.780
in a very unbiased way.

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:07.020
They were done with large scale screens

00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:09.160
of all sorts of inflammatory markers.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:11.290
There was no specific hypothesis going in.

00:03:11.290 --> 00:03:15.330
It was purely exploratory,
but the data are very clear.

00:03:15.330 --> 00:03:17.270
It doesn't mean you shouldn't
eat fiber doesn't mean

00:03:17.270 --> 00:03:18.450
that fiber is bad,

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:20.550
but it really shows that
eating fermented foods,

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:22.210
just one or two servings a day,

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:25.010
and maybe even ramping up to
three or four servings per day

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:28.010
can be very beneficial for
many aspects of health.

