00:11:39.750 --> 00:11:42.383
brain to the body and the
body back to the brain.

00:11:43.470 --> 00:11:46.250
The system that's most often
associated with this is our

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:49.540
10th cranial nerve called the vagus nerve.

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:52.730
The word vagus relates
to the word vagabond,

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:57.530
which to wander, and indeed
the vagus nerve is a vast,

00:11:57.530 --> 00:12:00.810
enormous wandering set of
nerves, so it's not one nerve.

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:02.820
It's not like one fiber, one axon.

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:05.170
As we say in the nervous
system, we have these wires,

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:07.560
we call axons that let
neurons communicate.

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:09.270
It's a bunch of neurons and a bunch

00:12:09.270 --> 00:12:11.550
of wires that go everywhere,
so where do they go?

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:14.493
Well they leave the
brain, and the brain stem,

00:12:14.493 --> 00:12:17.430
the brain stem is kind of
the back of your brain.

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:18.550
If you touch the back of your neck,

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:22.070
it's about three inches deep
to where you're touching.

00:12:22.070 --> 00:12:24.090
The neurons that are there

00:12:24.090 --> 00:12:26.210
send information into the body

00:12:26.210 --> 00:12:29.430
to control your bodily organs,
how fast your heart is,

00:12:29.430 --> 00:12:31.700
beating how fast you're breathing,

00:12:31.700 --> 00:12:34.070
how fast your digestion is occurring.

00:12:34.070 --> 00:12:35.930
Even things like whether
or not you are going

00:12:35.930 --> 00:12:38.470
to secrete so-called killer cells,

00:12:38.470 --> 00:12:42.960
your immune cells from your
spleen to go ward off bacteria.

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:46.100
Now the neurons there don't
know what to do unless they

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:49.170
receive information about
what's going on within the body

00:12:49.170 --> 00:12:52.200
and within the body, your heart,
your lungs, your diaphragm,

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:54.610
your gut, so everything
from your intestines

00:12:54.610 --> 00:12:55.993
to your stomach, et cetera,

00:12:57.520 --> 00:12:59.710
and your spleen or sending
information also up to the brain.

00:12:59.710 --> 00:13:02.530
So as I mentioned before,
it's a two-way street.

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:05.280
So the vagus nerve is
a very important nerve,

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:08.300
but just by saying vagus nerve,
it sounds like a singular.

00:13:08.300 --> 00:13:09.640
It sounds like one thing,

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:11.870
but actually what we're
talking about is a series

00:13:11.870 --> 00:13:13.780
of super highways, it's like Google maps,

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:15.080
it's got stuff going everywhere

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:17.943
with alternate routes,
communicating back and forth.

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:22.340
There are two fundamental
features of what's going

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:25.310
on in your body that
need to be communicated

00:13:25.310 --> 00:13:28.450
to your brain, these neurons
in your brain stem in order

00:13:28.450 --> 00:13:31.640
for your brain and your body
to work together correctly.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:35.390
And the two types of information
are mechanical information.

00:13:35.390 --> 00:13:37.550
So things like pressure,

00:13:37.550 --> 00:13:42.350
things like lack of pressure
and chemical information,

00:13:42.350 --> 00:13:44.320
whether or not your gut is acidic

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:46.630
or whether or not it's not acidic,

00:13:46.630 --> 00:13:49.613
whether or not you have some
sort of pathogen, you know,

00:13:50.890 --> 00:13:52.360
something that you ate or that
got into your body somehow

00:13:52.360 --> 00:13:55.080
and is making you sick or whether or not

00:13:55.080 --> 00:13:57.110
you don't have a pathogen in your body.

00:13:57.110 --> 00:14:00.020
So you've got mechanical
sensing and chemical sensing.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:01.290
So when you think about your sense

00:14:01.290 --> 00:14:04.070
of self and your ability
to understand what's going

00:14:04.070 --> 00:14:07.030
on in your body, if you feel
good, or if you feel bad,

00:14:07.030 --> 00:14:10.010
your sense of self is
dependent on these mechanical

00:14:10.010 --> 00:14:12.890
phenomenon and these chemical phenomenon.

00:14:12.890 --> 00:14:15.950
And for every organ in your body,

00:14:15.950 --> 00:14:18.060
whether or not that's
your heart or your lungs

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:22.020
or your spleen, both the
mechanical information about

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:27.020
that organ for instance, is
if your gut is full or empty,

00:14:28.190 --> 00:14:30.860
whether or not your heart is
beating fast or beating slowly,

00:14:30.860 --> 00:14:33.680
that's mechanical, and
chemical information,

00:14:33.680 --> 00:14:36.360
whether or not your gut feels
nice, and whether, you know,

00:14:36.360 --> 00:14:37.560
when I say nice, I mean,

00:14:38.575 --> 00:14:40.810
whether or not it has a balance
of acidity and alkalinity,

00:14:40.810 --> 00:14:43.210
that feels right to you or
whether or not your gut feels

00:14:43.210 --> 00:14:45.730
off, it doesn't feel quite right.

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:47.770
That's chemical information.

00:14:47.770 --> 00:14:50.340
If you are not getting enough oxygen

00:14:50.340 --> 00:14:53.540
and levels of carbon dioxide
and other gas go up too high.

00:14:53.540 --> 00:14:55.710
So your lungs can register

00:14:55.710 --> 00:14:59.030
that and that chemical
information is sent to your brain.

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:02.180
And then your brain does
certain things actually really

00:15:02.180 --> 00:15:03.630
encourages you to do certain things

00:15:03.630 --> 00:15:05.403
in order to adjust that chemistry.

00:15:06.950 --> 00:15:09.210
So the first principle that
everyone should understand about

00:15:09.210 --> 00:15:12.890
their sense of self is that
they are sensing mechanical

00:15:12.890 --> 00:15:15.940
and chemical information about every organ

00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:19.540
in their body, except for
one, and that's the brain.

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:22.240
Your brain actually doesn't
have pain receptors.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:24.040
It doesn't even have touch receptors.

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:25.840
The brain is a command center.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:29.180
It helps drive and govern changes
in the organs of the body.

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:30.970
But your brain doesn't
move, at least not much.

00:15:30.970 --> 00:15:33.530
It can move a little bit
fluid moves within it.

00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:36.500
But as long as you're healthy,
it's not moving that much.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:38.570
Your brain has no sensation

00:15:38.570 --> 00:15:41.970
of its own, in fact, when they
do brain surgery on people,

00:15:41.970 --> 00:15:45.070
they will the size or put
some anesthesia on the scalp.

00:15:45.070 --> 00:15:46.070
They'll cut away the skin there

00:15:46.070 --> 00:15:47.853
so that people don't feel anything.

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:50.260
They'll use some anesthesia
they'll peel back the skin

00:15:50.260 --> 00:15:52.156
and then they'll use a,

00:15:52.156 --> 00:15:54.660
let's call it what it is, it's a bone saw.

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:58.000
And they basically saw open
a little window in the skull.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.040
I've actually done this
before and seen this before.

00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:01.860
I've done this many times before,

00:16:01.860 --> 00:16:03.980
and once you're inside the brain,

00:16:03.980 --> 00:16:06.980
you can put electrodes in
there and you can put various

00:16:06.980 --> 00:16:09.860
things in there, of course,
all for therapeutic purposes.

00:16:09.860 --> 00:16:12.980
And you do that without any
anesthesia to the actual brain

00:16:12.980 --> 00:16:17.180
tissue, because it has no
receptors to sense anything.

00:16:17.180 --> 00:16:18.950
It doesn't have pain receptors.

00:16:18.950 --> 00:16:20.300
It doesn't have pressure receptors.

00:16:20.300 --> 00:16:22.080
None of that, when you have a headache

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:24.540
in your head, feels like
it's too much pressure,

00:16:24.540 --> 00:16:27.770
well that's because of here's
that lie outside the brain.

00:16:27.770 --> 00:16:29.840
So your organs are different.

00:16:29.840 --> 00:16:32.090
They need to tell your
brain what's going on.

00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:35.940
And there are ways that you
can control the mechanical

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:38.510
and the chemical state of your organs

00:16:38.510 --> 00:16:41.650
in ways that are very
powerful, and this is crucial

00:16:41.650 --> 00:16:45.990
to do, because if you can
properly regulate the mechanical

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:47.130
and chemical environment

00:16:47.130 --> 00:16:49.983
of your body, your brain functions better.

00:16:50.900 --> 00:16:52.980
This is absolutely clear from data

00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:54.360
that if your gut is healthy,

00:16:54.360 --> 00:16:57.760
if you get the alkalinity
right, the acidity, right,

00:16:57.760 --> 00:16:59.290
and if your spleen is healthy

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:01.840
and happy, and if your
lungs are working properly,

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:04.210
not just breathing and
pumping in and out air,

00:17:04.210 --> 00:17:06.450
but you're breathing at the
right cadence for a particular

00:17:06.450 --> 00:17:09.750
activity, then your brain
will function better.

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:13.000
So let's talk about how you
can adjust the mechanical

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.300
and chemical environment of your organs

00:17:15.300 --> 00:17:17.000
in order to make your brain better

00:17:18.036 --> 00:17:19.390
and how your brain can make the mechanical

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:23.540
and chemical environment within
your organs function better.

00:17:23.540 --> 00:17:26.200
For instance we're going to talk about

00:17:26.200 --> 00:17:28.350
how you can change the
chemistry of your gut in order

00:17:28.350 --> 00:17:31.320
for your brain to be able to
focus better, think better,

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:33.270
remember better and sleep better.

00:17:33.270 --> 00:17:35.420
And we're going to talk
about how you can change

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:37.930
the chemistry of other
organs in your body,

00:17:37.930 --> 00:17:40.060
such that your immune
system will function better

00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:41.283
than it would otherwise.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:44.100
And you can actually heal
faster from small cuts and

00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:47.940
bruises, but also injuries of
any kind, even major injuries.

00:17:47.940 --> 00:17:51.900
So as I mentioned before,
we've got these organs,

00:17:51.900 --> 00:17:54.160
the heart, the lungs, the diaphragm,

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:57.810
and I'll explain what that
is, the gut and the spleen.

00:17:57.810 --> 00:17:59.540
And the spleen is this immune organ.

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:04.240
Let's take one example of these
and explain how mechanical

00:18:04.240 --> 00:18:07.430
and chemical information
from this particular set

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:10.040
of organs communicates to the brain

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:12.460
and how that changes how our brain works.

00:18:12.460 --> 00:18:15.100
And the organ I'd like to focus on first

00:18:15.100 --> 00:18:17.550
are the lungs and the diaphragm.

00:18:17.550 --> 00:18:19.900
So we're all familiar with
our lungs, these two big bags

00:18:19.900 --> 00:18:21.510
of air, but they're actually
not two big bags of air.

00:18:21.510 --> 00:18:23.860
They actually have little
tiny sacs within them,

00:18:23.860 --> 00:18:25.640
actually millions of little sacs

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:27.710
called the alveoli of the lungs.

00:18:27.710 --> 00:18:28.680
The alveoli of the lungs

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:30.693
are like little tiny balloons
throughout our lungs,

00:18:30.693 --> 00:18:32.560
and the more of those balloons, we have,

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:34.340
the more air that we can actually contain.

00:18:34.340 --> 00:18:37.700
So we are not too big bags
of air in there, our lungs,

00:18:37.700 --> 00:18:40.700
we actually have millions and
millions of little tiny bags

00:18:40.700 --> 00:18:42.033
of air within those lungs.

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:47.450
Those little bags of air can
fill up or they can deflate,

00:18:47.450 --> 00:18:49.700
right, just like your
lungs overall can fill up

00:18:49.700 --> 00:18:51.210
or they can deflate.

00:18:51.210 --> 00:18:54.660
The diaphragm is a muscle, it's
kind of shaped like a dome.

00:18:54.660 --> 00:18:55.870
So it's kind of a, you know,

00:18:55.870 --> 00:18:58.870
think about a basketball or a soccer ball

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:01.320
that has most of the air pushed out of it.

00:19:01.320 --> 00:19:04.110
And so it's kind of crescent
shape or dome shaped,

00:19:04.110 --> 00:19:07.257
and it sits below our lungs
and the way the diaphragm

00:19:07.257 --> 00:19:09.460
and the lungs work together
is very interesting.

00:19:09.460 --> 00:19:11.400
The diaphragm is actually
skeletal muscles.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:13.580
So it's just like a bicep or a quadricep.

00:19:13.580 --> 00:19:16.160
And the fact that it is
skeletal muscle is important

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:18.640
because it has a unique property,

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:21.120
which is that you can
control it voluntarily.

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:23.560
You can decide to take control

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:25.830
of your diaphragm by just
consciously deciding you want

00:19:25.830 --> 00:19:27.380
to breathe in a particular way,

00:19:28.380 --> 00:19:30.070
just like you can take conscious
control over your legs.

00:19:30.070 --> 00:19:31.680
They will work just fine,
if you're not thinking

00:19:31.680 --> 00:19:33.630
about them, as you walk as
provide, you already know

00:19:33.630 --> 00:19:36.135
how to walk, but at any moment,

00:19:36.135 --> 00:19:36.968
you can decide to change the rate

00:19:36.968 --> 00:19:40.090
of your walking, your
so-called cadence of walking.

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:42.780
So the diaphragm as a
skeletal muscle also has

00:19:42.780 --> 00:19:44.860
that property, the diaphragm moves up

00:19:44.860 --> 00:19:46.770
and down, depending on how you breathe,

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:49.740
or rather, I should say
how the diaphragm moves up

00:19:49.740 --> 00:19:51.960
and down determines how you breathe.

00:19:51.960 --> 00:19:54.220
How you breathe is also dependent
on little muscles that are

00:19:54.220 --> 00:19:58.160
between your ribs, the
intercostals and other muscles,

00:19:58.160 --> 00:20:00.540
if you're a martial arts fan
that Bruce Lee was famous

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:04.400
for having these very pronounced
intercostals from doing all

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:06.850
sorts of, you know, bridging
exercise, et cetera.

00:20:06.850 --> 00:20:08.320
But those are the muscles.

00:20:08.320 --> 00:20:10.410
And we all have them, even if some

00:20:10.410 --> 00:20:14.780
of us, most of us don't have,
intercostals like Bruce Lee.

00:20:14.780 --> 00:20:17.590
So when you breathe a
couple things happen,

00:20:17.590 --> 00:20:20.040
but let's talk about the
mechanical things first.

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:23.310
And then let's talk about how
those mechanical steps relate

00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:26.570
back to the brain and what
that does for the brain.

00:20:26.570 --> 00:20:28.130
And I can promise you that

00:20:28.130 --> 00:20:31.310
if you develop an awareness
of these mechanical changes,

00:20:31.310 --> 00:20:35.100
you do not have to go through
extensive breathwork practice

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:37.050
or do extensive breathwork.

00:20:37.050 --> 00:20:40.980
You will immediately believe
it or not develop a sense

00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:44.510
of your breathing self of
your lungs and diaphragm.

00:20:44.510 --> 00:20:46.800
It takes no practice, but once you do it,

00:20:46.800 --> 00:20:49.300
you will forever be changed
in terms of your awareness of

00:20:49.300 --> 00:20:51.810
your breathing and your ability
to leverage your breathing.

00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:54.000
Kind of like the steering
wheel on a car in order

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.670
to shift your brain in the
direction that you want to go.

00:20:56.670 --> 00:20:58.480
So it's a very powerful system.

00:20:58.480 --> 00:21:00.340
And the way it works is the following.

00:21:00.340 --> 00:21:03.887
And this will also
incorporate the heart, so,

00:21:03.887 --> 00:21:06.270
and by the heart, I don't mean
it in the emotional sense.

00:21:06.270 --> 00:21:08.500
Although we don't rule out emotions here

00:21:08.500 --> 00:21:10.760
at the Huberman Lab
podcast, we like emotions,

00:21:10.760 --> 00:21:13.710
but I'm talking about the heart

00:21:13.710 --> 00:21:17.410
as an organ, as a beating
organ, that circulates blood.

00:21:17.410 --> 00:21:22.410
So when we inhale, these little
sacs in our lungs fill up

00:21:22.450 --> 00:21:24.480
and our lungs expand.

00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:28.370
And when we do that, we take
up space in our thoracic cavity

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:32.880
and our diaphragm moves down, okay.

00:21:32.880 --> 00:21:35.730
When we exhale, the diaphragm moves up,

00:21:35.730 --> 00:21:37.470
the lungs get smaller, okay?

00:21:37.470 --> 00:21:40.130
So inhales, diaphragm moves down.

00:21:40.130 --> 00:21:41.963
Exhales, diaphragm moves up.

00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:45.470
This actually controls our heart rate,

00:21:45.470 --> 00:21:49.040
but it does it by changing
the way that our brain works.

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:50.770
And it works in the following way.

00:21:50.770 --> 00:21:55.110
So when we inhale, our lungs
fill our diaphragm moves down.

00:21:55.110 --> 00:21:57.140
Our heart actually has a little more space

00:21:57.140 --> 00:21:59.010
because the diaphragm's moved down.

00:21:59.010 --> 00:22:01.720
So the heart gets a little
bit bigger, physically bigger,

00:22:01.720 --> 00:22:04.700
not in the emotional sense,
but physically bigger.

00:22:04.700 --> 00:22:05.810
And as a consequence,

00:22:05.810 --> 00:22:10.130
whatever blood is in the
heart flows at a slower rate

00:22:10.130 --> 00:22:13.550
because it's a larger volume,
so bigger volume heart,

00:22:13.550 --> 00:22:17.360
same amount of blood inside
the heart means slower flow.

00:22:17.360 --> 00:22:19.340
Okay, sort of like expanding a pipe.

00:22:19.340 --> 00:22:21.590
The brain registers that
because there are a set

00:22:21.590 --> 00:22:24.570
of neurons in the heart
called the sinoatrial node.

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:26.723
It sends that information to the brain.

00:22:27.650 --> 00:22:30.380
That information is registered
by the brain and the brain

00:22:30.380 --> 00:22:34.720
sends a message back to the
heart to speed the heart up.

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:38.290
So every time you inhale because
of these mechanical changes

00:22:38.290 --> 00:22:40.410
in the diaphragm and lungs,

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:43.400
and because of the mechanical
changes in the heart,

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:46.470
your brain sends a signal to
the heart to speed the heart

00:22:46.470 --> 00:22:51.470
up, so if you do long inhales
or you inhale more vigorously,

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:54.520
you actually are speeding your heart up.

00:22:54.520 --> 00:22:56.930
Now, of course you have to exhale as well.

00:22:56.930 --> 00:22:59.423
But for instance, if I were
to inhale very long like

00:22:59.423 --> 00:23:00.870
[inhales heavily]

00:23:00.870 --> 00:23:02.810
the entire time my heart
rate is increasing.

00:23:02.810 --> 00:23:04.571
And then if I did a quick exhale,

00:23:04.571 --> 00:23:05.450
[exhales quickly]

00:23:05.450 --> 00:23:08.015
something else will happen,
but if I kept doing that,

00:23:08.015 --> 00:23:10.470
[inhales heavily, exhales quickly]

00:23:10.470 --> 00:23:12.120
my heart rate would increase.

00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:14.170
It's not going to increase
linearly and forever,

00:23:14.170 --> 00:23:17.050
but it will increase with each inhale.

00:23:17.050 --> 00:23:18.855
Or I can simply make my
inhales more vigorous.

00:23:18.855 --> 00:23:20.070
[inhales quickly]

00:23:20.070 --> 00:23:21.560
And my heart rate will speed up.

00:23:21.560 --> 00:23:25.380
This is an autonomic and
automatic relationship

00:23:25.380 --> 00:23:29.170
between the diaphragm, the
lungs, the brain, and the heart.

00:23:29.170 --> 00:23:32.000
Now, if inhale speed the heart
up, what happens on exhales?

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:36.110
When we exhale, the diaphragm moves up.

00:23:36.110 --> 00:23:37.200
It's a little counterintuitive,

00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:39.050
but you can kind of think about it

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:41.240
as like pushing the plunge
on a syringe, right?

00:23:41.240 --> 00:23:42.550
When you exhale,

00:23:42.550 --> 00:23:46.890
this thing moves up and
as the diaphragm moves up,

00:23:46.890 --> 00:23:49.320
the heart has less space.

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:51.410
Meaning it gets a little bit smaller,

00:23:51.410 --> 00:23:53.570
which means that whatever
volume of blood is inside the

00:23:53.570 --> 00:23:57.180
heart moves faster, through
that smaller volume,

00:23:57.180 --> 00:24:00.640
that information is sent to
the brain via these collection

00:24:00.640 --> 00:24:04.460
of neurons called the sinoatrial
node for you aficionados.

00:24:04.460 --> 00:24:08.730
The brain then sends information
via the vagus nerve back

00:24:08.730 --> 00:24:12.030
to the heart, to slow the heart down.

00:24:12.030 --> 00:24:15.010
So while inhales speed up the heart,

00:24:15.010 --> 00:24:18.370
that's the net effect
exhales, slow the heart down.

00:24:18.370 --> 00:24:20.010
And the reason they slow the heart down is

00:24:20.010 --> 00:24:24.130
because of a register in the
change in mechanical pressure

00:24:24.130 --> 00:24:26.810
between the diaphragm,
the lungs and the heart.

00:24:26.810 --> 00:24:29.100
So this is to me, the simplest

00:24:29.100 --> 00:24:30.930
and most straightforward example

00:24:30.930 --> 00:24:34.360
of how the brain is changing
the way our organs work,

00:24:34.360 --> 00:24:35.990
our heart in this case,

00:24:35.990 --> 00:24:39.900
according to changes in
mechanical interoception.

00:24:39.900 --> 00:24:42.740
Now, we're not always aware
of this, some of us are aware

00:24:42.740 --> 00:24:43.961
of it, some of us aren't.

00:24:43.961 --> 00:24:45.300
If you do it right now,

00:24:45.300 --> 00:24:47.410
you will be aware of
it, so you can try this.

00:24:47.410 --> 00:24:50.410
You can basically, this is an experiment

00:24:50.410 --> 00:24:53.640
or an example in interoception,
in sensing one's self.

00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:56.180
So if you inhale, doesn't
matter how long you inhale.

00:24:56.180 --> 00:24:58.097
I'll do it for a couple seconds

00:24:58.097 --> 00:24:59.532
[inhales quickly]

00:24:59.532 --> 00:25:01.048
and then exhale twice as long.

00:25:01.048 --> 00:25:02.490
[exhales slowly]

00:25:02.490 --> 00:25:05.090
Nose or mouth, doesn't
matter, the entire time

00:25:05.090 --> 00:25:08.090
that you're exhaling, you're
slowing your heart down.

00:25:08.090 --> 00:25:10.800
So just as a car has an
accelerator and a brake,

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:13.750
or you can slow a car by
coming off the accelerator.

00:25:13.750 --> 00:25:14.583
When you exhale,

00:25:14.583 --> 00:25:16.540
you're effectively coming
off the accelerator,

00:25:16.540 --> 00:25:18.410
or if you want to think
about it differently,

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:19.610
you're hitting the brake,

00:25:19.610 --> 00:25:21.720
you're slowing down your heart rate.

00:25:21.720 --> 00:25:24.389
Now, normally your heart
rate stays in more or less

00:25:24.389 --> 00:25:26.250
the same range for a given activity

00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:28.500
because you're inhaling and exhaling.

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:30.490
But this is just a simple way of showing

00:25:30.490 --> 00:25:34.240
that mechanical changes in
your viscera can change the way

00:25:34.240 --> 00:25:35.290
that your brain works

00:25:36.410 --> 00:25:37.920
and then your brain changes the
way that those viscera work.

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:40.440
And it's a very concrete agreement,

00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:42.380
it's like a contract between the organs

00:25:42.380 --> 00:25:44.400
of your body and the brain.

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:47.320
In fact, you can think about
this contract in more detail,

00:25:47.320 --> 00:25:49.490
and you can leverage this
in a very powerful way

00:25:49.490 --> 00:25:51.423
to set the conditions of your mind.

00:25:52.630 --> 00:25:56.300
If you want to be more
calm, emphasize exhales,

00:25:56.300 --> 00:25:57.440
and the simplest way to do this.

00:25:57.440 --> 00:25:59.430
I've talked about this many times before,

00:25:59.430 --> 00:26:00.680
but if you haven't heard me say it,

00:26:00.680 --> 00:26:02.440
this will become immediately clear is

00:26:02.440 --> 00:26:04.520
to emphasize exhales through

00:26:06.230 --> 00:26:07.223
what's called a physiological sigh.

00:26:08.346 --> 00:26:09.610
Two inhales, could be through
the nose of the mouth,

00:26:09.610 --> 00:26:13.797
but ideally through the nose,
so [inhales quickly twice]

00:26:13.797 --> 00:26:15.640
so followed by a long
exhale. [exhales slowly]

00:26:15.640 --> 00:26:17.493
Those double inhales are
kind of important because

00:26:17.493 --> 00:26:20.000
what they do is they maximally
fill all those little sacs

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.580
in your lungs, and then
when you breathe out,

00:26:22.580 --> 00:26:26.040
you're exhaling as much of
the so-called carbon dioxide

00:26:26.040 --> 00:26:27.190
in your system as possible.

00:26:27.190 --> 00:26:29.170
We'll talk about carbon oxide in a second.

00:26:29.170 --> 00:26:33.840
So the fastest way to calm
down is to emphasize exhales.

00:26:33.840 --> 00:26:35.163
When you make exhales longer,

00:26:35.163 --> 00:26:38.230
you're slowing your heart
rate, you're calming down.

00:26:38.230 --> 00:26:39.900
You don't need any sophisticated training.

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:41.830
You don't have to do
this for minutes on end.

00:26:41.830 --> 00:26:42.750
You don't have to do anything.

00:26:42.750 --> 00:26:44.665
You don't even have to call it breathwork.

00:26:44.665 --> 00:26:46.670
It's just respiration, and in
fact, you do this every night.

00:26:46.670 --> 00:26:49.530
When you go to sleep and carbon
dioxide builds up too much

00:26:49.530 --> 00:26:50.363
in your bloodstream,

00:26:50.363 --> 00:26:52.220
or if you hold your breath or something,

00:26:52.220 --> 00:26:56.460
or you watch an animal or a
small child that sleeping,

00:26:56.460 --> 00:26:58.990
they will occasionally do these
double inhale long exhales

00:26:58.990 --> 00:27:00.480
it's way of slowing the heart down

00:27:00.480 --> 00:27:02.603
and eliminating carbon oxide.

00:27:03.620 --> 00:27:05.550
The opposite is also true.

00:27:05.550 --> 00:27:08.230
If you inhale deeply or vigorously

00:27:09.070 --> 00:27:13.190
and then exhale less
long or less vigorously,

00:27:13.190 --> 00:27:15.740
you will increase your level
of alertness through these

00:27:15.740 --> 00:27:19.940
purely mechanical aspects
of your interoception.

00:27:19.940 --> 00:27:23.107
So for instance, if I were
to take a big deep inhale

00:27:23.107 --> 00:27:25.754
[inhales deeply] and then a short exhale,

00:27:25.754 --> 00:27:27.445
[exhales quickly] and then
another one, a big inhale,

00:27:27.445 --> 00:27:28.740
[inhales deeply] short
exhale, [exhales quickly]

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:31.107
It only takes two or three of those

00:27:31.107 --> 00:27:32.580
before you start to feel more alert.

00:27:32.580 --> 00:27:34.400
And that's because your
heart rate is increasing.

00:27:34.400 --> 00:27:36.642
And actually if you keep doing that

00:27:36.642 --> 00:27:39.112
for 25 or 30 breaths of
inhale deep short exhale,

00:27:39.112 --> 00:27:42.010
you will start to secrete
a lot of adrenaline.

00:27:42.010 --> 00:27:43.560
This hormone that comes from your kidneys

00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:46.660
and from your brainstem
make you feel really alert.

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:49.580
You will actually feel as if
you've had a cup of espresso.

00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:52.380
So you will immediately wake up.

00:27:52.380 --> 00:27:54.390
And there's an intermediate form

00:27:54.390 --> 00:27:56.410
of breathing, which is
sometimes called box breathing,

00:27:56.410 --> 00:27:59.550
but it's really equal
inhale and exhale duration.

00:27:59.550 --> 00:28:01.190
And these, it basically goes like this.

00:28:01.190 --> 00:28:03.340
You're you're going to inhale,
so do this for maybe two,

00:28:03.340 --> 00:28:06.458
three seconds inhale, [inhales]

00:28:06.458 --> 00:28:08.978
then hold, okay, two, three seconds.

00:28:08.978 --> 00:28:10.578
Then exhale, two, three seconds.

00:28:11.470 --> 00:28:13.080
Then hold two, three seconds.

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:14.730
Most often people forget to hold.

00:28:15.680 --> 00:28:18.070
So it's inhale, hold, exhale, hold

00:28:18.070 --> 00:28:20.720
for equal or more or less equal durations,

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:22.270
could be one second, could be two seconds,

00:28:22.270 --> 00:28:23.370
could be three seconds.

00:28:23.370 --> 00:28:25.360
Most people find that when you get

00:28:25.360 --> 00:28:27.565
out past five seconds,
they start to struggle

00:28:27.565 --> 00:28:28.883
to maintain the so-called box breathing.

00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:31.550
And most people can't
consciously box breathe

00:28:31.550 --> 00:28:34.110
for too terribly long without
having to think about it.

00:28:34.110 --> 00:28:39.000
But the point here is that
through purely mechanical means

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.840
changing the way that you
breathe, emphasizing inhales

00:28:41.840 --> 00:28:43.280
or exhales, or keeping them the same

00:28:43.280 --> 00:28:46.190
will change the way that your brain works,

00:28:46.190 --> 00:28:47.840
how alert you are and how
well you function in anything.

00:28:47.840 --> 00:28:51.190
And again, this doesn't mean
that breathwork has no value.

00:28:51.190 --> 00:28:54.460
It's just simply to say
that long extended protocols

00:28:54.460 --> 00:28:56.150
of breathwork are simply,

00:28:56.150 --> 00:28:59.090
they are truly simply just
an exploration of this

00:28:59.090 --> 00:29:01.580
fundamental relationship
between the mechanics

00:29:01.580 --> 00:29:04.080
of your internal organs and your brain

00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:07.140
and how your brain controls
those internal organs.

00:29:07.140 --> 00:29:11.750
Now you might ask, well,
how is this pressure known?

00:29:11.750 --> 00:29:14.530
How does the body actually know
how full the lungs are, now?

00:29:14.530 --> 00:29:17.430
This is an answer that's more
for the aficionados out there,

00:29:17.430 --> 00:29:18.580
but I've had a few requests,

00:29:18.580 --> 00:29:21.110
or I should say thousands of
requests for more in-depth

00:29:21.110 --> 00:29:24.290
science, so if you're not
interested more in depth science,

00:29:24.290 --> 00:29:27.550
just this will allow you to
tune out now for maybe just 10

00:29:27.550 --> 00:29:30.080
seconds, and if you are
interested, pay careful attention,

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:32.846
there is a set of receptors

00:29:32.846 --> 00:29:35.300
which are called piezo receptors,

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:39.800
P-I-E-Z-O piezo receptors,
piezo means pressure.

00:29:39.800 --> 00:29:41.890
And these were discovered
a few years ago by a couple

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:44.960
of different laboratories,
but one of the main ones,

00:29:44.960 --> 00:29:46.767
one of the main laboratories

00:29:46.767 --> 00:29:47.970
that discovered these piezo receptors

00:29:47.970 --> 00:29:50.570
is the laboratory of Ardem Patapoutian.

00:29:50.570 --> 00:29:51.580
I love saying his name,

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:53.570
even though I'm probably pronouncing it,

00:29:53.570 --> 00:29:56.320
he's a friend and a former
colleague when my lab was down

00:29:56.320 --> 00:29:58.810
in San Diego, he's at
the Scripps Institute,

00:29:58.810 --> 00:30:01.280
he's a Howard Hughes Medical
Institute investigator,

00:30:01.280 --> 00:30:04.100
which basically means
that he's a total stud

00:30:04.100 --> 00:30:06.650
of science and has made
many important discoveries.

00:30:07.510 --> 00:30:11.480
The piezo receptors line many tissues,

00:30:11.480 --> 00:30:14.290
and inform the brain about
pressure in those tissues.

00:30:14.290 --> 00:30:16.600
But the lungs have a particular category

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:19.740
of piezo receptors called
piezo two receptors.

00:30:19.740 --> 00:30:23.440
And as you fill your lungs
and these little sacs

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:26.860
of air, the alveoli fill,
the piezo two receptors

00:30:28.070 --> 00:30:29.740
because of the way they
react to that filling

00:30:29.740 --> 00:30:33.640
send information by way
of a bunch of neurons,

00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:35.990
a bunch of wires up to the
brain and tell you how full your

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:38.330
lungs are, so that's the
kind of mechanistic detail.

00:30:38.330 --> 00:30:39.590
If you want to learn more about that,

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:43.610
you can look up our
Ardem's lab at the Scripps

00:30:43.610 --> 00:30:45.770
and the beautiful work that
they and other laboratories

00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:48.420
are doing on piezos,
piezos are pretty cool.

00:30:48.420 --> 00:30:50.250
I think I also just like saying piezo,

00:30:50.250 --> 00:30:52.320
so that's why I brought that up as well.

00:30:52.320 --> 00:30:56.630
So mechanical sensing of the
lungs, heart and diaphragm.

00:30:56.630 --> 00:30:58.320
And now let's talk about chemical sensing

00:30:58.320 --> 00:31:00.600
because there's carbon
dioxide and there's oxygen.

00:31:00.600 --> 00:31:02.380
And this is really simple.

00:31:02.380 --> 00:31:06.270
You have oxygen and carbon
dioxide and you need them both.

00:31:06.270 --> 00:31:08.230
I sometimes hear people
talk about carbon dioxide

00:31:08.230 --> 00:31:11.040
is this bad thing and
oxygen, it has a good thing.

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:12.475
You need them both,

00:31:12.475 --> 00:31:13.930
and you need them in
the appropriate balance.

00:31:13.930 --> 00:31:17.430
You have a collection of neurons
in your brain that register

00:31:17.430 --> 00:31:21.230
when carbon dioxide levels
get to a certain point

00:31:21.230 --> 00:31:23.070
in your bloodstream.

00:31:23.070 --> 00:31:25.890
When that point, that
threshold is reached,

00:31:25.890 --> 00:31:27.040
these neurons fire,

00:31:27.040 --> 00:31:29.440
and they cause you to
breathe sometimes called

00:31:29.440 --> 00:31:32.330
the gasp reflex, it just
makes you want to inhale.

00:31:32.330 --> 00:31:35.860
And as a consequence,
you bring in more oxygen.

00:31:35.860 --> 00:31:38.600
Okay, so we don't really
breathe to get oxygen.

00:31:38.600 --> 00:31:43.600
That's a by-product of inhaling
to eliminate carbon dioxide.

00:31:44.150 --> 00:31:47.150
You don't want carbon dioxide
levels to go too high.

00:31:47.150 --> 00:31:50.320
In fact, if you want to freak
somebody out and we do these

00:31:50.320 --> 00:31:52.430
in experiments, and I don't
recommend you do this,

00:31:52.430 --> 00:31:54.940
you just increase the levels
of carbon dioxide that they

00:31:54.940 --> 00:31:58.850
inhale, and the brain will go
into an almost immediate panic

00:31:58.850 --> 00:32:02.170
response because the health
of all our tissues depends on

00:32:02.170 --> 00:32:04.840
keeping a nice balance between
carbon dioxide and oxygen.

00:32:04.840 --> 00:32:07.380
You don't want carbon dioxide
levels to go too high.

00:32:07.380 --> 00:32:10.410
So the impulse to breathe,
if you're under water,

00:32:10.410 --> 00:32:13.150
or if you hold your breath is triggered

00:32:13.150 --> 00:32:16.320
by these neurons and the
triggering of those neurons comes

00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:18.910
from elevated carbon
dioxide in the bloodstream.

00:32:18.910 --> 00:32:21.440
And for those of you that don't quite know

00:32:21.440 --> 00:32:23.020
how to conceptualize the relationship

00:32:23.020 --> 00:32:25.040
between bloodstream and breath,

00:32:25.040 --> 00:32:26.290
I do think it's important.

00:32:26.290 --> 00:32:27.970
And maybe you remember this
from high school biology,

00:32:27.970 --> 00:32:29.030
but if you don't,

00:32:29.030 --> 00:32:31.300
I'll make it clear for
you now, it's very easy.

00:32:31.300 --> 00:32:36.300
You inhale air and that air
and the oxygen molecules

00:32:36.660 --> 00:32:38.100
in that air actually move

00:32:38.100 --> 00:32:40.030
from your lungs into the bloodstream

00:32:41.373 --> 00:32:43.381
because these little alveoli of the lungs,

00:32:43.381 --> 00:32:44.990
those little sacs of air are in there,

00:32:44.990 --> 00:32:48.640
they basically have a lot
of little micro vessels

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:52.500
and capillaries, little tiny,
basically blood vessels,

00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:54.140
essentially, although
they're mostly capillaries,

00:32:54.140 --> 00:32:56.815
micro capillaries are
the little tiny ones,

00:32:56.815 --> 00:32:58.050
that line them, so there's actually

00:32:58.050 --> 00:33:01.350
an interface and opportunity for air

00:33:01.350 --> 00:33:04.300
and molecules within the
air to pass into the blood

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:07.540
and then they move in your
bloodstream, and when you exhale,

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:08.710
the opposite is true.

00:33:08.710 --> 00:33:10.640
So you can move things from the air,

00:33:10.640 --> 00:33:13.740
into your bloodstream or from
your bloodstream into the air

00:33:13.740 --> 00:33:16.650
by way of the lungs, and
there's a lot more detail to it.

00:33:16.650 --> 00:33:18.960
And I'm sure those of you
that are experts out there.

00:33:18.960 --> 00:33:20.540
If you want to put some
stuff in the comments,

00:33:20.540 --> 00:33:23.020
maybe a little bit of a kind
of intermediate tutorial,

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:25.720
you might even entitle
it, intermediate tutorial.

00:33:25.720 --> 00:33:27.960
If you know a lot about
this, just I'll check it,

00:33:27.960 --> 00:33:29.210
but make sure you get the details, right.

00:33:29.210 --> 00:33:31.200
Make sure you know the process.

00:33:31.200 --> 00:33:33.910
And I find that for
people that are interested

00:33:33.910 --> 00:33:35.880
in understanding how
breathing really works,

00:33:35.880 --> 00:33:38.630
it's really nice to think
about the relationship

00:33:38.630 --> 00:33:41.418
between the heart and the vascular system,

00:33:41.418 --> 00:33:44.420
the blood and the air system,
the respiration system,

00:33:44.420 --> 00:33:48.170
and breathing, because those
two things are very, we say,

00:33:48.170 --> 00:33:51.340
they're interdigitated, they're
interwoven with one another.

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:55.290
So how does this work, well,
carbon dioxide is too high,

00:33:55.290 --> 00:33:57.080
you breathe in, you inspire, you,

00:33:57.080 --> 00:33:59.470
inhale you off as a consequence,

00:33:59.470 --> 00:34:02.030
when you exhale, you
offload carbon dioxide.

00:34:02.030 --> 00:34:04.320
There's a really cool way
that you can explore this

00:34:04.320 --> 00:34:06.380
chemistry of your breathing
and your bloodstream

00:34:06.380 --> 00:34:08.381
and the way that your brain works

00:34:08.381 --> 00:34:10.715
in ways that can really
benefit your health.

00:34:10.715 --> 00:34:12.300
And it works the following way.

00:34:12.300 --> 00:34:15.010
You want to essentially sit or lie down.

00:34:15.010 --> 00:34:16.283
It doesn't really matter.

00:34:17.200 --> 00:34:19.980
You definitely don't want
to be anywhere near water,

00:34:19.980 --> 00:34:22.690
not a bathtub, not a hot
tub, not a, you know,

00:34:22.690 --> 00:34:24.270
not a cold dunk or something.

00:34:24.270 --> 00:34:26.730
In fact, don't even be in a puddle.

00:34:26.730 --> 00:34:28.000
And what you want to do

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:30.905
in this case is you're
going to breathe in deep.

00:34:30.905 --> 00:34:32.750
So that's going to increase
your heart rate and then exhale

00:34:32.750 --> 00:34:35.110
passively by just letting
air fall out of your mouth.

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:36.753
So it will look something like this.

00:34:36.753 --> 00:34:38.090
[inhales vigorously, exhales passively]

00:34:38.090 --> 00:34:39.720
So it's you breathe in vigorously

00:34:39.720 --> 00:34:43.830
and then you let the air
just fall out of your mouth.

00:34:43.830 --> 00:34:45.110
When you do that,

00:34:45.110 --> 00:34:46.730
what you're essentially
doing is you're bringing

00:34:46.730 --> 00:34:49.310
in a lot of oxygen
through that deep breath.

00:34:49.310 --> 00:34:53.610
And you're exhaling a little
bit of that carbon dioxide.

00:34:53.610 --> 00:34:57.370
But if you were to repeat
it 25 times, maybe 30 times,

00:34:57.370 --> 00:35:00.860
it doesn't matter if it's 25
or 30, somewhere in there,

00:35:00.860 --> 00:35:03.730
you would essentially start
bringing in a lot of oxygen

00:35:03.730 --> 00:35:07.330
and blowing off or exhaling
a lot of carbon dioxide.

00:35:07.330 --> 00:35:09.900
So you're actually going
to change the chemistry

00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:13.090
of your internal landscape,
and you can then sense it.

00:35:13.090 --> 00:35:15.880
You can interocept what that is like.

00:35:15.880 --> 00:35:18.040
And there are some really
interesting reasons

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.240
for wanting to do that, so
I'm not going to do all 25

00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:21.680
or 30 now, maybe do five or 10,

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:23.960
so you can get a sense
of what it looks like,

00:35:23.960 --> 00:35:25.280
so that it's clear.

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:27.988
I'm going to essentially
demonstrate now, so it's inhale,

00:35:27.988 --> 00:35:28.990
[inhales vigorously]

00:35:28.990 --> 00:35:32.634
exhale through the mouth,[exhales]
I am inhaling the nose,

00:35:32.634 --> 00:35:37.634
[inhales vigorously, exhales
passively multiple times]

00:35:40.083 --> 00:35:43.660
So it's essentially, excuse
me, a two second or so inhale

00:35:43.660 --> 00:35:46.070
and then a one second or so
exhale, and as I was doing that,

00:35:46.070 --> 00:35:48.278
I can kind of feel my face get
flush and my body is heating

00:35:48.278 --> 00:35:50.860
up and my brain is heating
up, what's happening there?

00:35:50.860 --> 00:35:53.170
Well that pattern of breathing

00:35:53.170 --> 00:35:55.130
is increasing levels of adrenaline

00:35:55.130 --> 00:35:58.063
in my brain and body, and
I'm getting more alert.

00:35:59.250 --> 00:36:03.743
Then after 25 or 30 of those,
you exhale all your air.

00:36:03.743 --> 00:36:05.050
[exhales deeply]

00:36:05.050 --> 00:36:06.477
You dump all your air.

00:36:06.477 --> 00:36:08.970
You can do that, your nose or your mouth.

00:36:08.970 --> 00:36:11.200
And then you hold your
breath with your lungs empty

00:36:11.200 --> 00:36:13.760
for about 15 to 30 seconds.

00:36:13.760 --> 00:36:15.120
Now, for those of you that want

00:36:15.120 --> 00:36:17.930
to explore this, and please be
careful as you explore this,

00:36:17.930 --> 00:36:19.679
don't do anything stupid,

00:36:19.679 --> 00:36:22.290
like do this while you're
driving or something like that.

00:36:22.290 --> 00:36:24.230
You can exhale all your air

00:36:24.230 --> 00:36:26.330
and what you'll find then
is you can hold your breath

00:36:26.330 --> 00:36:28.840
for a very long time.

00:36:28.840 --> 00:36:32.700
And the reason you can do that
is because you've blown off

00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:35.740
all the carbon dioxide or
most of the carbon dioxide

00:36:35.740 --> 00:36:36.573
in your bloodstream.

00:36:36.573 --> 00:36:39.880
So you shifted the chemistry of your blood

00:36:39.880 --> 00:36:42.380
by breathing in a particular way.

00:36:42.380 --> 00:36:43.350
And by doing that,

00:36:43.350 --> 00:36:45.910
you are no longer triggering these neurons

00:36:45.910 --> 00:36:49.620
that cause the gasp reflex
or the reflex to breathe.

00:36:49.620 --> 00:36:51.210
Now, of course you have
to breathe sooner or later

00:36:51.210 --> 00:36:54.270
but what you'll find is if
normally your ability to hold

00:36:54.270 --> 00:36:57.410
your breath is a minute or
so before you really feel

00:36:57.410 --> 00:36:59.300
that gasp reflex kick in,

00:36:59.300 --> 00:37:02.330
you might find that you can
go 90 seconds or two minutes.

00:37:02.330 --> 00:37:03.250
And with some practice,

00:37:03.250 --> 00:37:04.820
people find that they can
start holding their breath

00:37:04.820 --> 00:37:06.170
for three or four minutes or longer.

00:37:06.170 --> 00:37:07.900
This is actually how free
divers do what they do.

00:37:07.900 --> 00:37:10.250
I do not want anyone free diving.

00:37:10.250 --> 00:37:11.610
If you're going to learn free diving,

00:37:11.610 --> 00:37:13.650
please learn it from an expert.

00:37:13.650 --> 00:37:16.230
Many people die trying to teach
themselves out of free dive

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:17.760
or trying to teach their
friends at a free dive

00:37:17.760 --> 00:37:19.320
when they don't know what they're doing.

00:37:19.320 --> 00:37:21.240
This is not what this
is about, don't again,

00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:22.720
don't do this anywhere near water,

00:37:22.720 --> 00:37:26.060
but it is a very interesting
exploration of how you can

00:37:26.060 --> 00:37:29.520
shift the chemistry of your
bloodstream by modulating your

00:37:29.520 --> 00:37:33.120
air by modulating the mechanics
of your diaphragm and lungs

00:37:33.120 --> 00:37:36.917
and thereby shift the way
your mind works, your brain.

00:37:36.917 --> 00:37:39.480
And in fact, what you'll
notice is that even though

00:37:39.480 --> 00:37:41.669
during that 25 or 30 breaths,

00:37:41.669 --> 00:37:43.430
[inhales and exhales quickly]

00:37:43.430 --> 00:37:47.240
you'll feel very alert,
when you exhale all your air

00:37:47.240 --> 00:37:50.560
and you're in the breath hold,
you will feel very alert,

00:37:50.560 --> 00:37:52.683
but very calm.

00:37:53.530 --> 00:37:55.040
Now this is interesting

00:37:55.040 --> 00:37:56.970
because it's a state that we all sort

00:37:56.970 --> 00:37:58.640
of want to achieve alert, but calm,

00:37:58.640 --> 00:38:00.250
but have a hard time achieving.

00:38:00.250 --> 00:38:03.010
And so for those of you that
have a hard time obtaining

00:38:03.010 --> 00:38:06.810
focus for sake of work or
focus for sake of anything I

00:38:06.810 --> 00:38:10.220
should say, and when you
are able to achieve focus,

00:38:10.220 --> 00:38:12.170
it's through the use of
things like stimulants,

00:38:12.170 --> 00:38:14.030
or you feel like you have
to have a cold shower

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:17.200
or ice bath, or you have to
have four espresso in order

00:38:17.200 --> 00:38:19.640
to be alert, but then you're
too alert, you're jittery.

00:38:19.640 --> 00:38:20.950
You can't focus.

00:38:20.950 --> 00:38:23.990
This pattern of breathing
can lend itself very well

00:38:23.990 --> 00:38:28.390
to entering states of alert,
but calm for the fall,

00:38:28.390 --> 00:38:31.180
the 10 or even 20 minutes
that follow that breathing.

00:38:31.180 --> 00:38:32.880
And then you could repeat it if you want.

00:38:32.880 --> 00:38:35.300
So it's a very useful practice to explore.

00:38:35.300 --> 00:38:36.670
Some of you may be familiar

00:38:36.670 --> 00:38:39.985
with this practice and
so-called Wim Hof breathing.

00:38:39.985 --> 00:38:41.750
Wim Hof is a practitioner of
what's called Tumo breathing.

00:38:41.750 --> 00:38:43.800
Tumo breathing has been
around for centuries.

00:38:43.800 --> 00:38:46.000
And for those of you that are familiar

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:49.120
with breathwork and yoga practices,

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:52.510
I acknowledged that nothing
I just described is new based

00:38:52.510 --> 00:38:54.164
on science, however,

00:38:54.164 --> 00:38:56.930
the science informs why
those practices work.

00:38:56.930 --> 00:38:59.890
And just as a little mini editorial,

00:38:59.890 --> 00:39:02.210
I just want to emphasize as well.

00:39:02.210 --> 00:39:05.790
That one thing that this podcast
is really about is trying

00:39:05.790 --> 00:39:08.400
to remove fancy nomenclature, whether

00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:11.120
or not it's yogic nomenclature
or scientific nomenclature

00:39:11.120 --> 00:39:13.684
so that people can access protocols.

00:39:13.684 --> 00:39:15.930
Because the moment we start
naming things after people

00:39:15.930 --> 00:39:19.250
or calling them Tumo et cetera,
I have no problem with that,

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:21.450
but it doesn't inform how
the practices are done,

00:39:21.450 --> 00:39:23.570
nor does it inform the
underlying mechanisms.

00:39:23.570 --> 00:39:25.860
So here I'm trying to
teach you the mechanisms.

00:39:25.860 --> 00:39:27.730
And as a final point to that,

00:39:27.730 --> 00:39:30.750
the most powerful form
of breathing is the one

00:39:30.750 --> 00:39:32.678
that takes into account

00:39:32.678 --> 00:39:35.270
the fundamental mechanisms
that in increase heart rate,

00:39:35.270 --> 00:39:39.480
that exhales decrease heart
rate, and that carbon dioxide

00:39:39.480 --> 00:39:43.330
and oxygen relate to the
bloodstream and the brain

00:39:43.330 --> 00:39:46.470
in particular ways, once you
understand those components,

00:39:46.470 --> 00:39:49.170
then you can create your own
so-called breathwork practices.

00:39:49.170 --> 00:39:51.930
You can breathe in the
ways that best serve you,

00:39:51.930 --> 00:39:55.230
as opposed to thinking that
one protocol is the best

00:39:55.230 --> 00:39:58.080
or holy protocol for everything,
because it's simply not.

00:39:59.330 --> 00:40:00.940
As a final final point,

00:40:00.940 --> 00:40:05.560
I want to say that as you
shift the way that you breathe,

00:40:05.560 --> 00:40:07.940
whether or not you're showing
off more carbon dioxide

00:40:07.940 --> 00:40:09.240
or bringing in more oxygen,

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:11.950
you are fundamentally
changing the chemistry

00:40:11.950 --> 00:40:14.250
of your internal milieu have your body,

00:40:14.250 --> 00:40:17.210
and that has been shown
to have important effects

00:40:17.210 --> 00:40:19.620
on the way that your immune
system functions and the way

00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:22.700
that you deal with
inflammation and all sorts

00:40:22.700 --> 00:40:25.750
of different sort of things
that can enter your body

00:40:25.750 --> 00:40:29.260
and cause problems or
conditions of stress, et cetera.

00:40:29.260 --> 00:40:32.190
So I will explore that further
as the episode goes on,

00:40:32.190 --> 00:40:35.920
but I want to move on to just
touch on one other aspect

00:40:35.920 --> 00:40:38.160
of reading, that's purely mechanical,

00:40:38.160 --> 00:40:39.410
which I think is very interesting

00:40:39.410 --> 00:40:42.980
and important, which relates
to a particular reflex

00:40:42.980 --> 00:40:45.250
that you're going to be very
familiar with in a second.

00:40:45.250 --> 00:40:48.730
And that can serve you very
well in times of extreme stress.

00:40:48.730 --> 00:40:50.100
The reflex I'm referring to

00:40:51.270 --> 00:40:52.790
is something called the
Hering Breuer Reflex.

00:40:52.790 --> 00:40:54.070
I'm not going to go into details

00:40:54.070 --> 00:40:55.960
about how the Hering Breuer reflex works,

00:40:55.960 --> 00:40:58.610
but it has to do with particular classes

00:40:58.610 --> 00:41:02.410
of neurons and cells that
are called a Baroreceptors.

00:41:02.410 --> 00:41:06.240
Those are basically pressure
receptors, they sense pressure.

00:41:06.240 --> 00:41:08.390
And basically what the
Hering Breuer reflex is

00:41:08.390 --> 00:41:11.340
about is that when your lung is inflated,

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:14.040
your desire to breathe is reduced.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:17.365
So you can try that
right now, you can inhale

00:41:17.365 --> 00:41:20.177
[inhales] huge big thing of air.

00:41:22.215 --> 00:41:23.457
And hold, okay?

00:41:23.457 --> 00:41:26.440
Your desire to breathe
will kick in later than

00:41:26.440 --> 00:41:31.430
were are you to exhale all
your air and hold your breath.

00:41:31.430 --> 00:41:34.220
When you exhale all your
air and your breath,

00:41:34.220 --> 00:41:36.470
unless you've done the sort
of protocol I described a few

00:41:36.470 --> 00:41:39.040
minutes ago of doing a bunch
of inhales and exhales first

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:42.070
in a very deliberate
way, you will feel empty.

00:41:42.070 --> 00:41:44.750
Those Baroreceptors are
going to be firing like crazy

00:41:44.750 --> 00:41:45.900
saying, there's no pressure in here,

00:41:45.900 --> 00:41:48.140
there's no pressure here,
I got nothing in here.

00:41:48.140 --> 00:41:49.480
You need to breathe,
you need to breathe in,

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:51.980
the gasp reflex will kick in sooner.

00:41:51.980 --> 00:41:55.730
You can apply that in all
sorts of situations related

00:41:55.730 --> 00:42:00.170
to exercise, related to
modulating stress, et cetera.

00:42:00.170 --> 00:42:03.260
So the Hering Breuer reflex
is a very powerful one.

00:42:03.260 --> 00:42:04.980
This is why you take a big deep breath

00:42:04.980 --> 00:42:06.858
before you go under
water. [inhales heavily]

00:42:06.858 --> 00:42:08.200
All right, you're not going

00:42:08.200 --> 00:42:10.040
to exhale all your air and go under water.

00:42:10.040 --> 00:42:12.530
If you were to exhale all
your air and go under water,

00:42:12.530 --> 00:42:14.790
you would absolutely feel
the need to come up sooner

00:42:14.790 --> 00:42:18.570
for a breath of air than
had you a full tank,

00:42:18.570 --> 00:42:21.610
so to speak a full of lungs full of air.

00:42:21.610 --> 00:42:24.560
And this is also the way
that people teach themselves

00:42:24.560 --> 00:42:26.710
to feel comfortable under water.

00:42:26.710 --> 00:42:27.700
So when you learn how to swim,

00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:29.290
you learn how to swim both by having air

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:31.930
in your lungs while you're
underwater and no air

00:42:31.930 --> 00:42:33.960
in your lungs while you're underwater.

00:42:33.960 --> 00:42:36.770
In any event the Hering
Breuer reflex is yet another

00:42:37.905 --> 00:42:40.470
dimension to the way that
mechanical pressure influences

00:42:40.470 --> 00:42:43.460
your brain's decision-making,
about what to do

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:46.220
with your body, in this case,
whether or not to breathe.

00:42:46.220 --> 00:42:48.640
So now I want to shift away from breathing

00:42:48.640 --> 00:42:52.210
and diaphragm and lungs and
move toward another organ

00:42:52.210 --> 00:42:55.290
within our viscera, which is our gut.

00:42:55.290 --> 00:42:56.370
So this includes our stomach

00:42:56.370 --> 00:42:59.580
and our intestines, our
esophagus and so forth.

00:42:59.580 --> 00:43:02.020
It's been said before,
both by me and by others

00:43:02.020 --> 00:43:05.130
that we are, but a series of
tubes, and indeed that's true.

00:43:05.130 --> 00:43:08.870
Believe it or not, every
system in your body is a tube.

00:43:08.870 --> 00:43:12.060
Your brain is actually a tube
that connects your spinal

00:43:12.060 --> 00:43:13.650
cord, which has also a tube.

00:43:13.650 --> 00:43:16.110
You started off as a tube,
you were like a churro.

00:43:16.110 --> 00:43:17.240
You know, those churros

00:43:17.240 --> 00:43:18.450
I don't know if you're
not familiar with churros,

00:43:18.450 --> 00:43:21.680
they're like donuts that
are shaped like a tube.

00:43:21.680 --> 00:43:24.080
That's essentially what you
look like early in development,

00:43:24.080 --> 00:43:27.790
not long after conception
and the front end

00:43:27.790 --> 00:43:30.080
of that churro grew and grew and grew,

00:43:30.080 --> 00:43:32.560
but you always maintained
a hollow through that tube.

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:35.960
That's why you have what are
called ventricles, gaps or a

00:43:35.960 --> 00:43:38.980
space in your brain and spinal
cord that run the length

00:43:38.980 --> 00:43:40.010
of your brain and spinal cord

00:43:40.010 --> 00:43:41.900
and fluid, cerebral spinal fluid,

00:43:41.900 --> 00:43:43.900
and other things move through that space.

00:43:43.900 --> 00:43:45.380
We're going to return
to the ventricles later,

00:43:45.380 --> 00:43:47.320
they are very important.

00:43:47.320 --> 00:43:51.580
They're just space filled
with fluid, but they do a lot.

00:43:51.580 --> 00:43:54.260
Similarly your digestive system

00:43:54.260 --> 00:43:56.150
starts with the tube at your mouth

00:43:57.090 --> 00:43:59.640
and of course goes down
through your throat.

00:43:59.640 --> 00:44:01.770
And then you've got all
the elements of the stomach

00:44:01.770 --> 00:44:04.340
and the intestines, and then
it comes out the other end.

00:44:04.340 --> 00:44:06.370
So you are, but a series
of different tubes,

00:44:06.370 --> 00:44:08.640
your vascular system, a
series of other tubes.

00:44:08.640 --> 00:44:10.123
So you're tubes.

00:44:11.360 --> 00:44:14.037
The way your digestive system works

00:44:14.037 --> 00:44:16.620
is to communicate to your brain

00:44:16.620 --> 00:44:19.470
about the status of the
mechanical pressures

00:44:19.470 --> 00:44:22.020
along this tube, so within your stomach

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:23.570
and your intestines, et cetera,

00:44:24.430 --> 00:44:27.680
and the chemical status of
that tube at various portions

00:44:27.680 --> 00:44:31.400
within that tube to inform your brain

00:44:31.400 --> 00:44:34.253
about how your brain
should control that tube.

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:39.093
So let's start with the
mechanical sensing of your gut.

00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:44.160
If you drink a lot of fluid,
or if you eat a lot of food,

00:44:44.160 --> 00:44:48.080
your gut will fill up, your
stomach will fill up with food.

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:50.290
Now it gets digested there.

00:44:50.290 --> 00:44:52.860
It gets digested elsewhere
along your digestive track too,

00:44:52.860 --> 00:44:55.430
of course but it starts
getting digested there

00:44:55.430 --> 00:44:57.095
because along this tube,

00:44:57.095 --> 00:44:59.720
you have a series of what
are called sphincters,

00:44:59.720 --> 00:45:01.970
which basically are
like little draw pulls.

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:03.210
Have you ever had a laundry bag,

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:04.400
which has a drawstring on it?

00:45:04.400 --> 00:45:06.140
You pull it and then it cinches shut,

00:45:06.140 --> 00:45:08.340
and then you can open it
again, that's what those are.

00:45:08.340 --> 00:45:11.350
Those are sphincter
openings and you have them

00:45:11.350 --> 00:45:14.770
in your throat, you have them
along your digestive tract,

00:45:14.770 --> 00:45:15.920
all the way to the end.

00:45:17.910 --> 00:45:20.100
Food will enter your gut.

00:45:20.100 --> 00:45:23.320
And if there's a lot of that
food, pressure receptors,

00:45:23.320 --> 00:45:26.770
some of which are these
piezo receptors will

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:28.930
communicate to the areas of
your brain that are involved

00:45:28.930 --> 00:45:31.930
in feeding, and we'll
say, don't eat anymore.

00:45:31.930 --> 00:45:33.660
You don't need to consume anymore, now,

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:35.940
some people bypass that these,

00:45:35.940 --> 00:45:38.530
I guess they have these like
hotdog eating competitions.

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:41.250
I'm always struck by how some
of those people are like,

00:45:41.250 --> 00:45:42.680
seem to be rail thin,

00:45:42.680 --> 00:45:47.060
but they actually train for
those competitions by ingesting

00:45:47.060 --> 00:45:49.870
large volumes of water, actually
a very dangerous practice.

00:45:49.870 --> 00:45:52.290
You can actually kill yourself
by drinking too much water,

00:45:52.290 --> 00:45:55.330
and you can kill yourself by
ingesting too much of anything,

00:45:55.330 --> 00:45:58.070
really to expand your
gut, not a good practice,

00:45:58.070 --> 00:46:00.100
not a big fan of those competitions.

00:46:00.100 --> 00:46:02.640
But even if you're one of those
people or you're the world

00:46:02.640 --> 00:46:03.930
heavyweight champion of them,

00:46:03.930 --> 00:46:06.400
they are informative
toward what I'm talking

00:46:06.400 --> 00:46:09.873
about now, which is that
as you expand the gut,

00:46:10.910 --> 00:46:12.760
a signal is sent by neurons,

00:46:12.760 --> 00:46:16.170
literally nerve cells that
are in the gut to the brain,

00:46:16.170 --> 00:46:18.510
stem up to the areas of
the brain that are involved

00:46:18.510 --> 00:46:20.560
in feeding, I did a
whole episode on feeding.

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:23.000
You can find on "Feeding,
Metabolism And Hunger."

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:25.780
You're welcome to listen to
that episode, if you like,

00:46:25.780 --> 00:46:28.880
and we'll shut down the
neurons that drive the desire

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:30.880
to put more stuff in your mouth.

00:46:30.880 --> 00:46:32.580
That thing that people say sometimes

00:46:32.580 --> 00:46:35.410
on well in this country frequently
after Thanksgiving meal,

00:46:35.410 --> 00:46:37.420
I can't put another bite in my mouth.

00:46:37.420 --> 00:46:40.500
Literally they shut down
some of the basic movements

00:46:40.500 --> 00:46:43.570
of the musculature to
take another fork bite.

00:46:43.570 --> 00:46:45.135
I know it sounds crazy,

00:46:45.135 --> 00:46:46.690
but they can actually control your brain.

00:46:46.690 --> 00:46:49.820
So your gut is so full that
it's controlling your brains,

00:46:49.820 --> 00:46:52.370
such that this action of spooning food

00:46:52.370 --> 00:46:54.310
towards your mouth is actually inhibited.

00:46:54.310 --> 00:46:57.663
It's made more difficult
or less likely to occur.

00:46:58.570 --> 00:46:59.660
It's incredible.

00:46:59.660 --> 00:47:03.140
The converse is also true, when
these piezo receptors signal

00:47:03.140 --> 00:47:06.220
to the brain, that the
gut is empty independent

00:47:06.220 --> 00:47:08.440
of your need, your actual need for food.

00:47:08.440 --> 00:47:11.490
There's a signal that sent to
your brain that says gut is

00:47:11.490 --> 00:47:14.520
empty and neurons get stimulated
in areas like the arcuate

00:47:14.520 --> 00:47:16.410
nucleus and these areas
of the hypothalamus

00:47:16.410 --> 00:47:21.100
and et cetera, that drive the
desire to make this action,

00:47:21.100 --> 00:47:25.430
to open the mouth and to put
stuff in it in particular food.

00:47:25.430 --> 00:47:28.330
So when you find yourself
at the refrigerator

00:47:28.330 --> 00:47:30.610
or you find yourself almost, you know,

00:47:30.610 --> 00:47:32.780
manically trying to get
food of different cons,

00:47:32.780 --> 00:47:34.220
you're not even thinking
about what you're eating,

00:47:34.220 --> 00:47:37.440
because you're so hungry, in
part that's because the lack

00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:41.470
of food in your gut has sent
that information to your brain

00:47:41.470 --> 00:47:44.660
and is driving particular
fixed action patterns

00:47:44.660 --> 00:47:46.210
that are associated with eating, in fact,

00:47:46.210 --> 00:47:48.430
one of the first things
children learn how to do is open

00:47:48.430 --> 00:47:50.460
their mouth when something
is presented to it.

00:47:50.460 --> 00:47:54.090
And then they learn how
to move a spoon or a fork.

00:47:54.090 --> 00:47:56.405
They're not very good at
it, at first, they get all

00:47:56.405 --> 00:47:57.540
over the place, but
eventually they get good at,

00:47:57.540 --> 00:47:58.670
or at least most people get good at

00:47:58.670 --> 00:48:00.570
if you watch how people eat, you know,

00:48:01.658 --> 00:48:02.643
it's kind of very variable out there.

00:48:04.960 --> 00:48:08.010
In any event, this is a
purely mechanical phenomenon.

00:48:08.010 --> 00:48:10.640
And this purely mechanical
phenomenon is driving our brain

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:12.910
to drive certain behavior.

00:48:12.910 --> 00:48:15.920
You can get better at registering sense

00:48:15.920 --> 00:48:20.470
of fullness or lack of fullness
in a very particular way.

00:48:20.470 --> 00:48:23.430
Some people have a very
keen sense of how full

00:48:23.430 --> 00:48:26.780
or empty their stomach is,
so if you've eaten anything,

00:48:26.780 --> 00:48:29.400
even if it's a small volume
of food in the last hour

00:48:29.400 --> 00:48:31.240
to three hours,

00:48:31.240 --> 00:48:33.920
it's actually a worthwhile
practice to take a few moments,

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:35.460
maybe 10, 20 seconds,

00:48:35.460 --> 00:48:39.650
and actually just try and
concentrate on sensing the neurons

00:48:39.650 --> 00:48:41.730
in your gut and how full
you are, like for instance,

00:48:41.730 --> 00:48:44.100
I ate a few hours ago and
then I had a little snack

00:48:44.100 --> 00:48:47.330
about 30 minutes ago or so.

00:48:47.330 --> 00:48:51.290
And my gut feels neither
terribly full nor terribly empty.

00:48:51.290 --> 00:48:56.030
It's kind of, I would put it
kind of like 30, 40% okay.

00:48:56.030 --> 00:48:59.088
So by just taking conscious awareness

00:48:59.088 --> 00:49:01.530
of how full or empty our gut is

00:49:01.530 --> 00:49:05.370
at various times between
meals, after a meal,

00:49:05.370 --> 00:49:09.600
before a meal, you can very
quickly develop a sense

00:49:09.600 --> 00:49:11.840
of how full or empty you are.

00:49:11.840 --> 00:49:12.800
Now, what's the consequence of that?

00:49:12.800 --> 00:49:14.870
The consequence of that is
actually rather interesting.

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:16.230
It's been shown that the consequence of

00:49:16.230 --> 00:49:19.460
that is actually that you can
better override the signals

00:49:19.460 --> 00:49:23.200
of these piezo receptors and
gut fullness or emptiness.

00:49:23.200 --> 00:49:25.170
So for those of you that
find that you eat kind

00:49:25.170 --> 00:49:28.190
of compulsively or non-consciously,

00:49:28.190 --> 00:49:30.180
or subconsciously, I should say,

00:49:30.180 --> 00:49:32.540
probably have to be conscious
enough to be awake to eat,

00:49:32.540 --> 00:49:34.457
but subconsciously you
just find yourself eating

00:49:34.457 --> 00:49:36.200
and here I'm describing myself, I'm like,

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:38.060
I'm a drive by blueberry eater.

00:49:38.060 --> 00:49:41.040
If there's a bowl of blueberries,
every time I walk past it,

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:42.380
I sort of have to grab a handful of them

00:49:42.380 --> 00:49:45.160
and pop them in my mouth,
but if you develop this sense

00:49:45.160 --> 00:49:48.900
of how much mecho-pressure,
it's not really word,

00:49:48.900 --> 00:49:53.020
but how much mechano-sensation
is in your gut, very quickly,

00:49:53.020 --> 00:49:55.010
you can learn to override that.

00:49:55.010 --> 00:49:57.409
You might ask, why would I
want to be able to override

00:49:57.409 --> 00:50:00.360
whether or not my stomach is
empty or my stomach is full?

00:50:00.360 --> 00:50:03.080
Well, there are many
reasons to want to do that.

00:50:03.080 --> 00:50:04.660
Many people right now are interested

00:50:04.660 --> 00:50:07.180
in so-called intermittent fasting.

00:50:07.180 --> 00:50:09.100
They're doing fast of
anywhere from 12 to 16 hours,

00:50:09.100 --> 00:50:12.150
every 24 hour cycle, that's
actually what my practice is.

00:50:12.150 --> 00:50:13.760
I do that on a regular
basis, sometimes the,

00:50:13.760 --> 00:50:15.335
I eat breakfast,

00:50:15.335 --> 00:50:16.890
but normally I pushed breakfast
out to about 11 or noon,

00:50:16.890 --> 00:50:18.100
or sometimes a little later,

00:50:18.100 --> 00:50:19.800
some people are doing longer fast,

00:50:20.905 --> 00:50:21.738
and there are really wonderful data

00:50:21.738 --> 00:50:24.760
publishing excellent
journals from my colleagues

00:50:24.760 --> 00:50:28.960
Satchin Panda at the Salk
Institute Of Biological Studies.

00:50:28.960 --> 00:50:31.090
And of course from other
laboratories showing that

00:50:31.090 --> 00:50:34.490
intermittent fasting can and
will have some positive health

00:50:34.490 --> 00:50:36.560
effects on things like liver health

00:50:36.560 --> 00:50:39.240
and brain health and
other aspects of health.

00:50:39.240 --> 00:50:41.830
Whether or not it's the
best form of dieting

00:50:41.830 --> 00:50:44.350
for the sake of losing weight,
that's very controversial,

00:50:44.350 --> 00:50:48.080
but it's clear that having
a period of fasting every 24

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:51.610
hours or perhaps even longer
from time to time can be

00:50:51.610 --> 00:50:54.750
beneficial because it stimulates
what's called autophagy,

00:50:54.750 --> 00:50:56.280
the clearing away,

00:50:56.280 --> 00:51:00.100
or the body's ability to
eat certain dead cells,

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:02.440
so called senescent cells,
and for many people,

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:06.450
they struggle with fasting
because they feel they have a

00:51:06.450 --> 00:51:09.550
very keen sense of their
stomach being empty.

00:51:09.550 --> 00:51:11.560
And they feel as if they have to eat.

00:51:11.560 --> 00:51:14.010
And in a kind of counter-intuitive way,

00:51:14.010 --> 00:51:15.710
there's some data that
indicate that being able

00:51:15.710 --> 00:51:18.010
to sense whether or not
your gut is full or empty,

00:51:18.010 --> 00:51:20.910
and just the knowledge that
that's communicating information

00:51:20.910 --> 00:51:23.780
to your brain about whether to not

00:51:23.780 --> 00:51:25.663
to eat or not just that awareness,

00:51:26.555 --> 00:51:28.380
that understanding allows
them to override the signal.

00:51:28.380 --> 00:51:29.213
They think, oh, you know,

00:51:29.213 --> 00:51:31.490
I'm not actually in need
of nutrients right now.

00:51:31.490 --> 00:51:33.490
It's just that my stomach is empty.

00:51:33.490 --> 00:51:35.770
And these piezo receptors,

00:51:35.770 --> 00:51:38.250
and some other ones that I'll
tell you about in a moment

00:51:38.250 --> 00:51:40.270
are signaling to my brain that it's empty.

00:51:40.270 --> 00:51:42.760
I don't actually need food, it's just,

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:44.480
it's just that my brain is reacting

00:51:44.480 --> 00:51:47.510
to the fact that my gut is deflated,

00:51:47.510 --> 00:51:50.380
so to speak or a smaller,
doesn't have food in it.

00:51:50.380 --> 00:51:53.010
So there are other ways that
our guts communicate with our

00:51:53.010 --> 00:51:55.650
brain, it's not just our
stomach talking to our brain.

00:51:55.650 --> 00:51:58.413
It's also our intestines
talk to our brain.

00:51:59.650 --> 00:52:02.660
The Liberles Lab the guy's
name is Steven Liberles,

00:52:02.660 --> 00:52:05.030
he runs a lab at Harvard Medical School,

00:52:05.030 --> 00:52:06.300
it's a terrific lab, does excellent work

00:52:06.300 --> 00:52:07.760
on gut, brain communication

00:52:07.760 --> 00:52:10.740
and other aspects of
viscera brain communication.

00:52:10.740 --> 00:52:12.130
They discovered a category

00:52:13.830 --> 00:52:16.433
of neurons called the GLP1R neurons,

00:52:16.433 --> 00:52:18.840
these are neurons that are basically

00:52:18.840 --> 00:52:20.700
in your neck, I mean, they're
part of the nervous system,

00:52:20.700 --> 00:52:23.460
but they're, you can, they
can be found near your neck.

00:52:23.460 --> 00:52:26.280
And those neurons send little wires down

00:52:26.280 --> 00:52:31.180
into the intestines and
deep into the stomach,

00:52:31.180 --> 00:52:35.130
but mostly into the intestines
and they sense stretch

00:52:35.130 --> 00:52:36.700
of your intestines.

00:52:36.700 --> 00:52:37.810
So this is pretty wild.

00:52:37.810 --> 00:52:40.390
These neurons sense how
stretched out your intestines are

00:52:40.390 --> 00:52:42.800
and how fast things are moving
through your intestines,

00:52:42.800 --> 00:52:44.780
slow or fast, or if there's nothing there.

00:52:44.780 --> 00:52:47.210
And then those neurons
send another branch,

00:52:47.210 --> 00:52:48.660
they have a branch in one direction,

00:52:48.660 --> 00:52:50.370
senses what's going on in your intestines.

00:52:50.370 --> 00:52:52.280
And they have another branch that goes up

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:55.310
from your neck in your brain
to either trigger the desire

00:52:55.310 --> 00:52:57.720
to eat more or just stop eating.

00:52:57.720 --> 00:52:59.100
So these are really cool neurons

00:52:59.100 --> 00:53:00.470
and they're basically stretch receptors.

00:53:00.470 --> 00:53:02.030
They look a lot like the piezo receptors

00:53:02.030 --> 00:53:05.090
that we talked about before,
so these GLP1R neurons

00:53:05.090 --> 00:53:09.170
are sensing stretch, so
purely mechanical sensing.

00:53:09.170 --> 00:53:10.900
And in addition to that,

00:53:10.900 --> 00:53:13.530
the Liberles Lab discovered neurons

00:53:13.530 --> 00:53:16.080
that detect nutrients themselves.

00:53:16.080 --> 00:53:17.680
Now, the main reason why we need

00:53:19.110 --> 00:53:21.620
to eat is to bring
nutrients into our body.

00:53:21.620 --> 00:53:24.030
And there is another set of neurons,

00:53:24.030 --> 00:53:25.740
those are called GPR65 neurons,

00:53:25.740 --> 00:53:28.050
if you want to know, but you
don't have to remember that,

00:53:28.050 --> 00:53:30.950
do the same thing in terms
of their connections.

00:53:30.950 --> 00:53:33.160
They send connections down into
the intestines and into the

00:53:33.160 --> 00:53:36.030
gut, into the stomach, but
mostly into the intestines.

00:53:36.030 --> 00:53:37.260
And then send that information back up

00:53:37.260 --> 00:53:39.880
to the brain as to whether or
not there are certain kinds

00:53:39.880 --> 00:53:42.140
of nutrients in our digestive track.

00:53:42.140 --> 00:53:44.380
Now, these neurons are the
ones to pay attention to

00:53:44.380 --> 00:53:46.370
if we're talking about chemical signaling

00:53:46.370 --> 00:53:48.230
and then in the next couple of minutes,

00:53:48.230 --> 00:53:52.810
I'm going to tell you about
how you can understand hunger

00:53:52.810 --> 00:53:55.890
and had a modulate your
hunger for the right foods,

00:53:55.890 --> 00:53:58.250
in fact, for healthy foods.

00:53:58.250 --> 00:54:02.420
The way this is done is
by leveraging the activity

00:54:02.420 --> 00:54:04.660
of these GPR65 neurons,

00:54:04.660 --> 00:54:07.556
these neurons that sense nutrients, okay.

00:54:07.556 --> 00:54:09.080
They're telling your brain

00:54:09.080 --> 00:54:11.560
what's in your gut and intestines,

00:54:11.560 --> 00:54:13.870
and you have another set of
neurons that were discovered

00:54:13.870 --> 00:54:16.330
by another guy he's
out at Duke University,

00:54:16.330 --> 00:54:18.320
his name is Diego, excuse me,

00:54:18.320 --> 00:54:22.620
Diego Borges he's a wonderful scientist.

00:54:22.620 --> 00:54:26.050
He has a degree in nutrition,
but also in neuroscience.

00:54:26.050 --> 00:54:28.763
And he found that there are
neurons that line the gut,

00:54:29.790 --> 00:54:32.870
and those neurons in
collaboration with these GPR65

00:54:32.870 --> 00:54:35.830
neurons are sensing
for three things, okay?

00:54:35.830 --> 00:54:38.550
So we say nutrients, which
nutrients are they looking for?

00:54:38.550 --> 00:54:40.420
What are these neurons
paying attention to?

00:54:40.420 --> 00:54:43.410
While these neurons are
activated by the presence

00:54:43.410 --> 00:54:47.790
of fatty acids in particular,
omega-3 fatty acids,

00:54:47.790 --> 00:54:51.300
sorts of things that come
from fatty fish, oil, krill,

00:54:51.300 --> 00:54:53.570
certain kinds of animal protein, animal,

00:54:53.570 --> 00:54:56.410
and plant substances.

00:54:56.410 --> 00:54:59.700
You can look up what has a
lot of omega-3s and those

00:54:59.700 --> 00:55:03.170
omega-3s make these neurons
fire electrically like crazy

00:55:03.170 --> 00:55:05.840
up to the brain and make you
want to eat more of those

00:55:05.840 --> 00:55:09.070
things, but it turns out in
pretty appropriate levels.

00:55:09.070 --> 00:55:12.540
These neurons also respond to amino acids.

00:55:12.540 --> 00:55:15.530
So when you eat a food,
it's broken down in the gut,

00:55:15.530 --> 00:55:16.520
actually the way it's
broken down in the gut

00:55:16.520 --> 00:55:17.670
is kind of interesting.

00:55:18.922 --> 00:55:20.950
Your gut basically cinches
off a sphincter up top,

00:55:20.950 --> 00:55:24.010
cinches off a sphincter below
it when there's food there.

00:55:24.010 --> 00:55:27.460
And then you have a
series of smooth muscles

00:55:27.460 --> 00:55:31.060
that tumble the food and literally
physically break it down.

00:55:31.060 --> 00:55:32.490
And then of course,

00:55:32.490 --> 00:55:33.930
enzymes come in and
start digesting the food.

00:55:33.930 --> 00:55:35.350
And we're going to talk about digestion

00:55:35.350 --> 00:55:37.290
and how that's communicated
to the brain in a moment.

00:55:37.290 --> 00:55:40.090
And for those of you with any
autoimmune issues or digestive

00:55:40.090 --> 00:55:43.180
issues, this is going to be
very important conversation.

00:55:43.180 --> 00:55:44.770
But meanwhile there are these neurons

00:55:44.770 --> 00:55:47.780
in the gut and as these fatty acids

00:55:47.780 --> 00:55:49.340
float out of the digested food,

00:55:49.340 --> 00:55:54.340
so literally fat molecules,
and as amino acids are coming

00:55:55.140 --> 00:55:58.000
from the proteins as
they're digested in the gut.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:00.040
And as a third food item,

00:56:00.040 --> 00:56:03.360
sugars are coming from
the foods that we eat.

00:56:03.360 --> 00:56:06.720
These neurons will fire a lot
to the brain that says, Hey,

00:56:06.720 --> 00:56:09.493
whatever you're doing up
there, do more of it, okay?

00:56:10.650 --> 00:56:11.950
Now the sugars are a
little bit cryptic because

00:56:11.950 --> 00:56:14.603
when I say sugars or I say amino acids,

00:56:15.542 --> 00:56:19.470
or I say fatty acids, this
has nothing to do with taste.

00:56:19.470 --> 00:56:21.690
In fact, beautiful
experiments have been done

00:56:21.690 --> 00:56:24.030
by the Borges Lab and
by other labs showing

00:56:24.030 --> 00:56:26.930
that even if you numb the mouth,

00:56:26.930 --> 00:56:29.280
even if you gavavge,
which is a really, just a,

00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:32.040
it's a fancy word for
basically tube feeding,

00:56:32.040 --> 00:56:33.170
you put a tube down into the gut,

00:56:33.170 --> 00:56:34.250
you just deliver the food to the gut.

00:56:34.250 --> 00:56:37.490
So you get no opportunity to
taste, it sounds pretty awful.

00:56:37.490 --> 00:56:41.100
If you force feed by gavage,
or you numb the mouth,

00:56:41.100 --> 00:56:43.720
these neurons don't care about the mouth.

00:56:43.720 --> 00:56:46.110
They only care about the
nutrients coming from these foods.

00:56:46.110 --> 00:56:48.990
And then they signal to the
brain, hey, do that thing, do

00:56:48.990 --> 00:56:51.940
that thing where you lift
that object, we call a fork

00:56:51.940 --> 00:56:54.480
or a spoon, do that thing
where you drink the milkshake,

00:56:54.480 --> 00:56:56.600
do that thing where you
move your mouth like this,

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:59.010
not talking, but do that
thing where you swallow.

00:56:59.010 --> 00:57:02.060
So that's how the nutrients
in our gut control us.

00:57:02.060 --> 00:57:05.440
And this is why for people
that experience extreme sugar

00:57:05.440 --> 00:57:07.620
cravings, or even mild sugar cravings,

00:57:07.620 --> 00:57:10.440
replacing those foods with
foods that have high levels

00:57:10.440 --> 00:57:14.250
of omega-3 or amino acids
can produce sugar cravings.

00:57:14.250 --> 00:57:16.690
And I've talked about this
on a previous episode,

00:57:16.690 --> 00:57:18.010
but if you didn't catch it, no big deal.

00:57:18.010 --> 00:57:20.770
I'll tell you right now
that for many people,

00:57:20.770 --> 00:57:23.840
the solution to sugar cravings
is to ingest a small amount,

00:57:23.840 --> 00:57:27.113
maybe a teaspoon or so of an
amino acid called glutamine.

00:57:28.090 --> 00:57:30.690
And if you have really
extreme sugar cravings,

00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:34.040
you can even mix that glutamine
with a full-fat cream,

00:57:34.040 --> 00:57:35.630
which actually makes it
taste pretty darn good.

00:57:35.630 --> 00:57:37.970
And you drink that anytime
you have a sugar craving

00:57:37.970 --> 00:57:38.907
or just a sip or two of that.

00:57:38.907 --> 00:57:40.980
And we find is that the
sugar cravings disappear,

00:57:40.980 --> 00:57:44.320
because you're basically
giving fat and amino acids

00:57:44.320 --> 00:57:47.010
to those neurons in the
gut and in the intestine,

00:57:47.010 --> 00:57:49.160
that signal to the brain
that you want more.

00:57:49.160 --> 00:57:50.230
Now, this doesn't give you a kind

00:57:50.230 --> 00:57:52.523
of runaway hunger for full fat cream.

00:57:53.626 --> 00:57:55.920
Although it will say when I
was in high school for various

00:57:55.920 --> 00:57:57.570
reasons, but mostly because
I liked the way it tastes.

00:57:57.570 --> 00:57:59.940
I was using half and half in my cereal.

00:57:59.940 --> 00:58:01.610
