01:01:01.220 --> 01:01:05.570
acid HCL and adjusting
gut acidity that way.

01:01:05.570 --> 01:01:07.740
And it was kind of frowned upon,

01:01:07.740 --> 01:01:10.375
now in looking over the
peer reviewed literature,

01:01:10.375 --> 01:01:12.010
it's clear that this business
of trying to make the gut a

01:01:12.010 --> 01:01:14.550
little more acidic is actually one way

01:01:14.550 --> 01:01:18.970
in which people treat or try
and ameliorate acid reflux.

01:01:18.970 --> 01:01:21.570
So it's kind of counterintuitive
increasing acidity in the

01:01:21.570 --> 01:01:24.260
gut to try and reduce acid
reflux, thought you're supposed

01:01:24.260 --> 01:01:27.720
to take antacids, well, the
field has shifted quite a bit.

01:01:27.720 --> 01:01:30.870
And so we're going to review
what it is to maintain the

01:01:30.870 --> 01:01:34.650
chemistry of the gut at a
slightly more acidic level

01:01:34.650 --> 01:01:36.480
or a more aesthetic level, I should say,

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:38.340
because it turns out
that there are a number

01:01:38.340 --> 01:01:41.300
of things that are in gut
are just call it what it is,

01:01:41.300 --> 01:01:43.650
it's gastric juice, sounds kind of gross.

01:01:43.650 --> 01:01:46.000
But gastric juices are actually

01:01:47.710 --> 01:01:49.193
powerful modulators of brain state.

01:01:50.150 --> 01:01:51.860
Put differently, one of the best things

01:01:51.860 --> 01:01:54.595
that you can do to have a healthy brain,

01:01:54.595 --> 01:01:55.686
a well-functioning brain

01:01:55.686 --> 01:01:57.366
and a healthy and well-functioning body

01:01:57.366 --> 01:01:59.450
is to maintain proper gut chemistry.

01:01:59.450 --> 01:02:02.910
And that's basically accomplished
by getting the right level

01:02:02.910 --> 01:02:05.423
of acidity and alkalinity in your gut.

01:02:06.360 --> 01:02:08.420
Now this is not quack pseudoscience.

01:02:08.420 --> 01:02:11.550
This is not based on cleanses
or anything of that sort.

01:02:11.550 --> 01:02:14.420
Well, we're going to talk about
now are peer reviewed data

01:02:14.420 --> 01:02:17.830
in very high quality journals,
like the Journal Cell,

01:02:17.830 --> 01:02:20.760
which is one of the three
apex science nature, so,

01:02:20.760 --> 01:02:22.220
and journals of that sort,

01:02:22.220 --> 01:02:25.180
that point to the gut
microbiome and its relationship

01:02:25.180 --> 01:02:28.850
to acidity of the gut and how
the gut microbiome can help

01:02:28.850 --> 01:02:32.820
enhance auto-immune function

01:02:32.820 --> 01:02:35.270
and various other aspects
of brain and body health.

01:02:35.270 --> 01:02:39.480
So within all the mucosal
lining tissues of our body,

01:02:39.480 --> 01:02:43.220
we have what are called
microbiota, little micro organisms

01:02:43.220 --> 01:02:44.630
that we didn't make that actually come

01:02:44.630 --> 01:02:49.630
from our environment or our
food and live inside us.

01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:53.490
And there are good microbiota
and there are bad microbiota

01:02:54.730 --> 01:02:58.000
whether or not we have good microbiota

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:01.180
or bad microbiota depends on one thing.

01:03:01.180 --> 01:03:04.400
And that one thing is how acid or alkaline

01:03:05.240 --> 01:03:07.193
the given mucosal tissue is.

01:03:08.300 --> 01:03:11.740
So we actually have a
microbiome in our nose.

01:03:11.740 --> 01:03:13.280
And just as a very brief aside,

01:03:13.280 --> 01:03:15.900
because I'd be remiss
if I didn't say this,

01:03:15.900 --> 01:03:18.630
if you emphasize nasal breathing most

01:03:18.630 --> 01:03:20.830
of the time, except
when speaking or eating.

01:03:21.730 --> 01:03:24.280
And if you downplay mouth breathing,

01:03:24.280 --> 01:03:25.950
meaning you refrain from mouth breathing,

01:03:25.950 --> 01:03:30.950
especially in sleep, you
improve the nasal microbiome.

01:03:32.060 --> 01:03:35.740
It gets better at fighting off infections.

01:03:35.740 --> 01:03:37.170
This was shown in a beautiful paper,

01:03:37.170 --> 01:03:39.640
published in Cell Reports last year.

01:03:39.640 --> 01:03:43.190
And that paper I should mention
was performed in humans.

01:03:43.190 --> 01:03:44.990
So you've got a microbiome in your nose

01:03:44.990 --> 01:03:47.270
and my nasal breathing most
of the time, not all the time.

01:03:47.270 --> 01:03:48.103
Cause there going to be times

01:03:48.103 --> 01:03:49.770
when you need to breathe
through your mouth

01:03:49.770 --> 01:03:51.430
for whatever reason, hard exercise

01:03:51.430 --> 01:03:53.380
or eating or speaking, but by
breathing through your nose,

01:03:53.380 --> 01:03:57.350
most of the time you are
creating an additional layer of

01:03:57.350 --> 01:04:00.660
immune defense against particles
that could get you sick.

01:04:00.660 --> 01:04:02.030
Whereas when you mouth breathe,

01:04:02.030 --> 01:04:04.040
you are taking down a layer of defense

01:04:04.040 --> 01:04:06.170
and you are putting yourself
more at risk of infection.

01:04:06.170 --> 01:04:07.670
This is what this paper shows.

01:04:09.810 --> 01:04:12.860
You also have a gut microbiome that is

01:04:13.880 --> 01:04:18.360
in your throat, in your
stomach and in your intestines.

01:04:18.360 --> 01:04:20.950
And that gut microbiome
is extremely powerful

01:04:20.950 --> 01:04:24.770
in regulating your mood
and your immune function.

01:04:24.770 --> 01:04:27.210
Now, this is not something
that you can sense directly.

01:04:27.210 --> 01:04:30.830
You don't know when you have a
bunch of good microbiota or a

01:04:30.830 --> 01:04:33.400
bunch of bad microbiota because
you can feel them moving

01:04:33.400 --> 01:04:35.210
around in there, actually
that would be pretty awful,

01:04:35.210 --> 01:04:37.023
that would be pretty creepy feeling.

01:04:38.910 --> 01:04:41.560
Rather that according to whether
or not your gut is alkaline

01:04:41.560 --> 01:04:43.860
or acidic in the appropriate ways,

01:04:43.860 --> 01:04:48.003
you will populate your gut with
the appropriate microbiota.

01:04:48.950 --> 01:04:52.960
So you want your stomach
to be pretty acidic,

01:04:52.960 --> 01:04:55.260
but other elements of your digestive tract

01:04:55.260 --> 01:04:57.220
are going to be more pH.

01:04:57.220 --> 01:04:58.930
And basically there's a gradient,

01:04:58.930 --> 01:05:03.930
meaning there's a low to high
pH gradient along the gut.

01:05:04.120 --> 01:05:05.770
You don't have to know what the pH

01:05:05.770 --> 01:05:08.140
should be at any one given point,

01:05:08.140 --> 01:05:10.460
because you're not going
to go and put microbiota

01:05:10.460 --> 01:05:12.490
at one location and not another.

01:05:12.490 --> 01:05:16.060
What you essentially want to
do is create an environment

01:05:16.060 --> 01:05:20.480
where the proper can thrive,
because when you do that,

01:05:20.480 --> 01:05:24.550
you greatly decrease what are
called inflammatory cytokines.

01:05:24.550 --> 01:05:26.970
So these are things that
are secreted both by cells,

01:05:26.970 --> 01:05:30.660
within the body and cells
within the brain to impact brain

01:05:30.660 --> 01:05:33.070
health and brain function
and bodily health.

01:05:33.070 --> 01:05:36.010
They go by particular name,
so there's something called

01:05:36.010 --> 01:05:38.670
TNF alpha, Tumor Necrosis Factor Alpha.

01:05:38.670 --> 01:05:40.050
It is inflammatory.

01:05:40.050 --> 01:05:43.040
It's not a good thing to
have at elevated levels.

01:05:43.040 --> 01:05:45.950
You have something called
Interleukin Six, IL-6

01:05:45.950 --> 01:05:47.580
also causes inflammation,

01:05:47.580 --> 01:05:50.080
causes damage to tissues,
not a good thing to have

01:05:51.030 --> 01:05:53.263
elevated for long periods of time.

01:05:54.220 --> 01:05:55.450
And then you have
anti-inflammatory cytokines,

01:05:55.450 --> 01:05:58.020
things like Interleukin 10,
which reduce inflammation.

01:05:58.020 --> 01:05:59.650
And there are hundreds of these,

01:05:59.650 --> 01:06:01.880
if not thousands of these
different cytokines,

01:06:01.880 --> 01:06:03.600
some of which promote inflammation,

01:06:03.600 --> 01:06:06.140
some of which reduce inflammation.

01:06:06.140 --> 01:06:11.120
The simple way to adjust these
things in the proper ratios

01:06:11.120 --> 01:06:13.070
is to adjust your gut microbiome.

01:06:13.070 --> 01:06:15.120
The best way to adjust your microbiome is

01:06:15.120 --> 01:06:17.570
to ingest certain types of foods.

01:06:17.570 --> 01:06:19.470
So there is a beautiful literature

01:06:19.470 --> 01:06:22.070
on this now, but the most
important literature is the one

01:06:22.070 --> 01:06:25.280
that I referred to at the
beginning of this episode,

01:06:25.280 --> 01:06:29.100
which is what to ingest
and what not to ingest

01:06:29.100 --> 01:06:33.010
in terms of foods in order
to create the best conditions

01:06:33.010 --> 01:06:35.270
in your gut so that you can
create the best conditions

01:06:35.270 --> 01:06:36.420
in your brain and body.

01:06:37.550 --> 01:06:39.560
There was a study done by my colleague,

01:06:39.560 --> 01:06:43.240
Justin Sonnenberg at
Stanford School of Medicine.

01:06:43.240 --> 01:06:45.660
Justin's actually my upstairs neighbor

01:06:45.660 --> 01:06:47.890
in the building at Stanford where I work

01:06:49.390 --> 01:06:51.230
and they explored how different foods

01:06:51.230 --> 01:06:53.800
or different diets, I should say,

01:06:53.800 --> 01:06:56.710
impact the gut microbiome
and inflammatory markers.

01:06:56.710 --> 01:06:58.460
And this is a beautiful
study because it was done

01:06:58.460 --> 01:07:00.710
in hundreds of human patients.

01:07:00.710 --> 01:07:02.510
These actually weren't
patients that were sick,

01:07:02.510 --> 01:07:06.320
I should say human subjects
that were otherwise healthy

01:07:06.320 --> 01:07:09.180
from a huge variety of
backgrounds, so you had men,

01:07:09.180 --> 01:07:10.960
you had women, you had people

01:07:10.960 --> 01:07:13.220
of different races, different ethnicities.

01:07:13.220 --> 01:07:14.690
You had a huge range of backgrounds

01:07:14.690 --> 01:07:16.140
and they tracked all of that.

01:07:17.350 --> 01:07:19.140
And what they did is they
explored two types of diets.

01:07:19.140 --> 01:07:21.180
One is a high fiber diet.

01:07:21.180 --> 01:07:25.670
So dietary fibers are
non-digestible are only partially

01:07:25.670 --> 01:07:27.960
digestible carbohydrates typically.

01:07:27.960 --> 01:07:29.660
And they compared that to diets

01:07:29.660 --> 01:07:33.420
that were unchanged, except
for the inclusion of a few,

01:07:33.420 --> 01:07:36.680
to a few more servings of
fermented foods, each day,

01:07:36.680 --> 01:07:39.010
things like sauerkraut,
things like kimchi,

01:07:39.010 --> 01:07:41.000
they even explored, it
sounds pretty disgusting

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:42.230
to me, but who knows, I've never tried it,

01:07:42.230 --> 01:07:44.680
which is fermented cottage cheese.

01:07:44.680 --> 01:07:47.460
And what they found was
that after initial period

01:07:47.460 --> 01:07:50.370
of a few weeks, where they
had people either eat a lot

01:07:51.310 --> 01:07:54.700
of fiber or eat one or two
servings of fermented foods,

01:07:54.700 --> 01:07:57.530
they had those people ramp
up their ingestion of either

01:07:57.530 --> 01:08:00.200
fiber or fermented foods, so
they kind of ease them into it.

01:08:00.200 --> 01:08:01.950
As they went baseline then ramp up

01:08:01.950 --> 01:08:04.400
to the point where they
were ingesting, you know,

01:08:05.427 --> 01:08:06.690
four or five servings of fiber or

01:08:07.817 --> 01:08:10.420
of fermented foods per day,
which sounds like a lot.

01:08:10.420 --> 01:08:12.670
But for fermented foods,
that would be, you know,

01:08:12.670 --> 01:08:16.170
four or five tablespoons
of sauerkraut or kimchi.

01:08:16.170 --> 01:08:17.737
It's not quite,

01:08:17.737 --> 01:08:20.140
it's not like huge platefuls
of fermented foods.

01:08:20.140 --> 01:08:22.440
And then they looked
at a number of things.

01:08:22.440 --> 01:08:23.760
They looked at the proteome,

01:08:23.760 --> 01:08:25.420
which is a kind of like
looking at the genome,

01:08:25.420 --> 01:08:27.640
but a bunch of proteins
that are made in the body.

01:08:27.640 --> 01:08:30.890
And they did this by fecal
samples, by stool samples,

01:08:30.890 --> 01:08:33.020
and they did this by blood
draw, which is great,

01:08:33.020 --> 01:08:34.410
it's a real power of this study.

01:08:34.410 --> 01:08:37.620
In fact, the most comprehensive
study that I'm aware of.

01:08:37.620 --> 01:08:40.450
By looking at these different
tissues across long periods

01:08:40.450 --> 01:08:44.990
of time, so many weeks, and
then returning people to their,

01:08:44.990 --> 01:08:47.410
to the diet that they were
on before they went into the

01:08:47.410 --> 01:08:51.430
study, they will were able
to establish in a causal way,

01:08:51.430 --> 01:08:55.730
how ingesting fibers or fibrous
foods versus ingesting these

01:08:55.730 --> 01:08:58.370
fermented foods on a daily
basis could impact the gut

01:08:58.370 --> 01:09:02.190
microbiome and many inflammatory markers

01:09:03.342 --> 01:09:05.612
and many markers of immune function

01:09:05.612 --> 01:09:07.970
and auto immune function.

01:09:07.970 --> 01:09:10.570
And the takeaway message
from this study is that the

01:09:10.570 --> 01:09:15.250
fermented foods far out
performed the high fiber diet.

01:09:15.250 --> 01:09:18.480
In fact, the high fiber diet
in some people was beneficial

01:09:18.480 --> 01:09:22.330
and in other people caused
issues with inflammation.

01:09:22.330 --> 01:09:25.127
This is very different than
what I was taught growing up

01:09:25.127 --> 01:09:26.743
and what many of us were taught.

01:09:27.750 --> 01:09:30.270
Interestingly they also
observed that people

01:09:30.270 --> 01:09:31.960
that ate the high fiber diet

01:09:31.960 --> 01:09:34.620
had increases in certain enzymes

01:09:36.020 --> 01:09:38.900
that lend themselves to better
digestion of carbohydrates.

01:09:38.900 --> 01:09:41.350
And I think there's an important
insight to come from this.

01:09:41.350 --> 01:09:43.350
Nowadays we kind of live
in the age of extremes

01:09:43.350 --> 01:09:45.610
where people seem to
either want to be carnivore

01:09:45.610 --> 01:09:47.320
or like never ingest a vegetable,

01:09:47.320 --> 01:09:49.350
I hear they don't even like allow pepper,

01:09:49.350 --> 01:09:51.620
but they're not even allowed, you know,

01:09:51.620 --> 01:09:54.720
sauerkraut or something like very extreme

01:09:54.720 --> 01:09:57.270
or pure plant based, pure vegan or pure.

01:09:57.270 --> 01:09:59.040
So essentially pure carbohydrate

01:09:59.040 --> 01:10:01.550
or pure animal protein, very extreme.

01:10:01.550 --> 01:10:03.970
I'm an omnivore, I like to eat a mixture

01:10:03.970 --> 01:10:06.130
of different things at
different times of days,

01:10:06.130 --> 01:10:09.560
but very extreme, but this is
interesting because what this,

01:10:09.560 --> 01:10:13.350
what these data show is that
perhaps ingesting a high

01:10:13.350 --> 01:10:16.040
carbohydrate high fiber diet,
which is really what these,

01:10:16.040 --> 01:10:18.480
the high-fiber condition really was

01:10:18.480 --> 01:10:22.530
actually makes people better
at digesting carbohydrates.

01:10:22.530 --> 01:10:23.363
This may explain

01:10:23.363 --> 01:10:27.050
why people who are used to
a, kind of a more paleo type

01:10:27.050 --> 01:10:29.950
